<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brief Middle East Economic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Foreign investments in Morocco increased by 132
percent in the first half of 1999 as compared to the corresponding
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign investments amounted to 4.1 billion dirhams
(about 420 million U.S. dollars) by the end of last June, the best
indicator since 1997 when foreign investments exceeded 1.2 billion
dirhams.
</P>
<P>
France ranked first on the list of investors in Morocco with
total investments amounting to 1.52 billion dirhams (about 160
million dollar). The United States was the second, followed by
Spain, Italy and Germany.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Ministry of Industry and Electricity has
allocated several plots of land to industrial investors in Riyadh,
Jeddah, Mecca, Al Qassim, Madina, Asseer and Ha'il.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" quotes the minister, Hashim
Abdulla Yamani, as saying that the total area allocated to each
industrial project amounted to about 4,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Chemical and plastic industries claimed the highest percentage
of projects that benefit from land distribution, namely, 42
percent, followed by mineral industries, 16 percent, engineering
and food industries, 14 percent and 10 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman is planing to set up permanent display
centers for its products in some of the key export markets such as
Yemen, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the Netherlands and South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The first of them will be opened soon in Rotterdam, the
Netherlands, a spokesman for the Oman Center for Investment
Promotion and Export Development was quoted by the UAE's Khaleej
Times daily as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"As Rotterdam is the gateway to Europe and other markets,
displaying their products at the Oman Business Center will help
Omani companies gain access to the huge market," the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
