<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Spanish Aerospace Concerns Prepare to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua)-The Daimler-Chrysler Aerospace
(DASA), the aerospace and defense unit of the German-U.S.
automotive giant Daimler-Chrysler, will merge with the Spanish
aerospace concern CASA in the next month, a high-ranking German
aerospace official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two partners are now close to the last stage of the fusion,
said Rolf Stuessel, deputy chairman of German Aviation and
Aerospace Association, at an aerospace congress in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
According to Stuessel and officials of DASA, the new
German-U.S.-Spanish aerospace concern will be named DASACASA,
which will be the third largest aerospace company with an annual
turnover of about 20 billion marks (11 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fusion is mainly aimed to strengthen German and Spanish
sides' weight while negotiating with their French and British
partners to transform the European Airbus consortium into a modern
joint-stock enterprise, Stuessel said.
</P>
<P>
After the merger, DASACASA will become the No.1 stockholder of
the Airbus with 42.1 per cent of the share. The Airbus, together
controlled by the DASA, the CASA, the US-British GEC/British
Aerospace and the French Aerospatiale Matra, is the world's second
largest aircraft manufacturer after Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The merger plan, first disclosed in this June, grew out of
DASA's failure to overtake British Aerospace last spring.
Disappointed by British Aerospace's quick tie-up with the U.S.
General Electric (GEC), DASA began the talks with CASA.
</P>
<P>
Asked why the partners in the Airbus consortium have not yet
brought out a detailed plan of structural alteration, Stuessel
said, "the will of the industry is just like before, but the steps
must also be supported by the politics."
</P>
<P>
The major problem lies in French government's much involvement
in Aerospatiale Matra and its opposition to the idea of
modernization, thus the Airbus remains a consortium, Stuessel
said.
</P>
<P>
The other three governments of the Airbus partners have
complained that the industrial side had found no concept on the
new structure of the Airbus, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
