<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Announces Measures to Protect Right of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin announced on Monday some measures to protect the right of
employment, including punishment for those who employ too many
workers on short-term contracts and lay off employees in an
abusive way.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the parliament deputies of the Socialist Party
in Strasbourg, Jospin said that the government will present a law
to punish financially the enterprises which employ short-term
contract workers in an excessive way.
</P>
<P>
He said that public aid will not go to those enterprises which
are laying off workers while making profits.
</P>
<P>
``It is inacceptable that an enterprises announce substantial
benefits and at the same time ask the government to pay for a part
of its restructuring leading to many layoffs,'' said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The Socialists were earlier embarrassed by the lack of
intervention from the prime minister after the Michelin tire group
announced earlier this month that it would lay off 7,500 workers
while its profits have risen 20 percent in the early half this
year.
</P>
<P>
Jospin was apparently trying to reaffirm the stand of the
leftwing government on employment, after being sharply criticized
by his major ally in the leftwing majority, the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the government will increase charges on those
enterprises which lay off workers, while decreasing charges on
those keeping employees and creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
``We want to install a link between the rise of contributions
to the charge of enterprises and their behavior in the field of
economic layoffs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the government will also provide life long job
trainings to workers to help them keep or find jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
