<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Firmly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) - European stock markets closed
firmly higher Monday, boosted by speculation over the strength of
the banking sector and Wall Street's opening rebound after last
week's falls.
</P>
<P>
Shares in the heavily weighted banks sector here continued to
surge ahead, dragging the wider market higher in the wake of last
Friday's hostile offer for NatWest from Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index closed at 6078.6, up 141 points, or 2.37
percent.
</P>
<P>
National Westminster Bank continued to dominate the market,
adding 9 percent to Friday's more than a third gain following an
unsolicited takeover offer by Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The boost came as expectations of a counter-bid, notably from
Royal Bank of Scotland, gained favor among investors.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt ended the session up 53.11 points
from Friday's close at 5239.64 after moving in a range of 5201.58
to 5247.63 during the day.
</P>
<P>
Veba stock rose 6 percent and Viag shares tumbled 14 percent
when the boards of the two German utilities confirmed their plans
to merge in a 14 billion US dollars deal.
</P>
<P>
In Paris share prices closed higher in relatively thin volume
as merger speculation lifted several shares in an otherwise
lackluster session.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index finished 58.43 points higher at 4596.60.
</P>
</TEXT>
