<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Mexico to Hold Talks on Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Mexico have decided to start on October 7 their eighth round of
talks on a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The EU said in a latest report that this round is considered as
"decisive" by all negotiators. The last round of negotiations in
July did not turn out to be very successful, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 9-day talks will conclude on pending issues, such as
industrial products, agricultural products, public procurement,
services and investment.
</P>
<P>
On industrial products, the EU said Mexicans are very reluctant
to open further their market to products from EU member countries.
In this case, the EU offer "is not that interesting to them since
they already benefit from the Generalized System of Trade
Preferences".
</P>
<P>
The EU's objective is clearly equivalence with the North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), "a target which Mexican
industry thinks is a bit much to swallow at once", the EU report
said.
</P>
<P>
EU negotiators fear that North American products might only get
a Mexican rubberstamp before being reexported to the EU,
encouraging trade deflation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of traded products have already been agreed on,
but some sensitive products such as textiles, motor vehicles and
agricultural products still need some discussion, it said.
</P>
<P>
The EU report also said the European Commission, the EU
executive body, has introduced a "conceptual breakthrough" in
making up its offer on services. Instead of offering a list of the
services it wants to liberalize, they came up with a "negative
list", outlining exemptions to liberalization, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This rather new approach is to be used in other trade
negotiations, but EU member states have had difficulties with it,
since they were afraid of "forgetting" something to be put on the
list, it said.
</P>
<P>
Mexicans and Europeans are to discuss these reciprocal negative
lists at their next round of negotiations, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
