<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government has decided to take a
series of actions against segments of the Islamic Movement which
are engaged in inciting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a special meeting Sunday night
convened at the request of the police and General Security
Service (GSS) in response to the involvement of Israeli Arabs
belonging to the Islamic Movement in the attempted car bombings in
Haifa and Tiberias earlier this month. (BC-Israel-Arabs)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman has been nominated
for the 1999 Nobel Peace Prize, according to letters of former
prize laureates obtained by the local daily the Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations have been submitted on his behalf by such
laureates as former U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali,
Palestinian leaer Yasser Arafat, South African Archbishop Desmond
Tutu and former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger.
(BC-Israel-Weizman)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has been re-elected
with 93.79 percent "Yes" votes in a referendum on his presidency,
the interior minister announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habib el-Adli said on national television that the "Yes" vote
stood at 17,554,856, or 93.79 percent of the valid votes in the
referendum on Sunday. The "No" vote was 1,162,525, or 6.21
percent, el-Adli said.
</P>
<P>
The 71-year-old sitting president was the only candidate in the
yes-or-no referendum.
</P>
<P>
The turnout was 79.2 percent, or 18.957,893 of the nearly 24
million eligible voters, the minister said.
(BC-Egypt-Presidential Referendum-Details)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman congratulated his
Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak on his re-election in a
nation-wide referendum held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Weizman telephoned Mubarak Monday afternoon and expressed his
congratulations to Mubarak that he has been re-elected to another
six-year term in office during the Sunday national referendum,
Weizman's office said.
</P>
<P>
During the cordial conversations, Mubarak also expressed
congratulation to Weizman on his nomination as a candidate for
1999 Nobel Peace Prize, it added. (BC-Israel-Egypt)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will be sworn in on
October 5 to serve his fourth six-year term, a presidential decree
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The People's Assembly, Egypt's parliament, will convene that
day an extraordinary session, during which Mubarak will be sworn
in, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
(BC-Egypt-Mubarak-Swearing-in) 
</P>
</TEXT>
