<HEADLINE> Zambia Launches Program on Title Deeds to Lands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Commission of Lands
has embarked on a program to educate people in both the rural and
urban areas of the country on the importance of having title deeds
to their lands.
</P>
<P>
Chief Registrar of Lands and Deeds Abdul Khan said here Monday
that about 90 percent of Zambians owning land have no title deeds
as most of the country's land is held under customary tenure.
</P>
<P>
The state has only eight percent of the country's land, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Khan said Zambia is an agricultural country so it is important
that people have titles to their lands as this will enable them to
acquire loans for land development and also to prevent ownership
wrangles in the future.
</P>
<P>
The commission has great respect for customary right but it is
retrogressive to possess land without title especially when there
are so many investors in the agriculture sector in search of land,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 75 million hectares of land in the country, 43
million hectares, or 56 percent, is available for agriculture, he
said, adding at present less than 10 percent of the 43 million
hectares has been utilized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
