<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Intensified International Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the special session of the General Assembly on
small islands, Chinese delegate Wang Guangya said given the
economic globalization is creating unprecedented fierce
competition, the international community should pay closer
attention to the disadvantaged and help the small island states
and the least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The international community, especially developed countries,
should honor their commitment, take concrete actions in
financial, technical and capacity building, so as to help small
island states overcome their difficulties, the Chinese delegate said.
</P>
<P>
The international community should encourage and support
small island states to formulate their own strategy for
sustainable development and establish an order of priority in
light of their national conditions and level of economic
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The international community should help small island states
overcome the challenges brought by economic globalization, and
help them explore and identify better ways to attract foreign
investment and create more trade opportunity, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Paints Mixed Picture of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Monday issued a report by Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the
progress in curbing conflict and promoting peace in Africa,
painting a mixed picture of what is like on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"Africa today, on the eve of the new millennium, reveals a
remarkable combination of accomplishments and unresolved problems,
of opportunities seized and chances missed," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The birth of so many new states in Africa this century, with
all the attendant euphoria and high expectations, has been quickly
followed by disillusionment and disappointment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are places in Africa where governments persist in
spending money on weapons they can ill afford for wars they should
not fight; where conflicts are seen as business opportunities for
arms merchants and rebel groups alike; where poor governance
deprives people of basic needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is place in Africa "where silence about AIDS exacerbates
the epidemic; where corruption thwarts economic growth; and where
crushing debt burdens, trade barriers and declining aid make it
extremely hard for African nations to attract investment and stave
off further marginalization from the global economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are, in short, places where the widely held view of
Africa as a region in perpetual crisis is not just an image but an
all-too-grim and painful reality," he said. "Civil war prevents
many sick, hungry civilians from receiving international
humanitarian assistance."
</P>
<P>
In April last year, Annan presented a report to both the
Security Council and the General Assembly, shedding light on the
causes of conflict in Africa and the promotion of durable peace
and sustainable development on the continent, where the least
developed countries outnumber the other parts in the world.
</P>
<P>
The report attracted wide interest and attention and has been
discussed and analyzed in various forums, within and outside the
United Nations system.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a very encouraging response to the report from
governments, research and academic institutions, civil society
groups, non-governmental organizations and individuals, many of
whom have used the debate surrounding the report as an opportunity
to contribute to the search for peace and development in Africa,"
Annan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Opposition Parties Launch Electoral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A former Mozambican rebel
movement and 10 minor opposition political parties Monday signed a
document to formally launch a union for contesting the forthcoming
presidential and parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The document, necessary for registering the Electoral Union
with the National Elections Commission (CNE), recognizes Afonso
Dhlakama, leader of the rebel movement Renamo (Resistencia
Nacional de Mozambique), as the president of the union and Renamo
General Secretary Joao Alexandre as the secretary.
</P>
<P>
The minor parties which have tied their fortunes to Renamo are
Mozambique United Front (MUF); National Convention Party (PCN);
Mozambican People's Progress Party (PPPM); Democratic Renewal
Party (PRD); Mozambique National Union (UNAMO); Mozambican
National Movement (MONAMO); Patriotic Action Front (FAP);
Independent Alliance of Mozambique (ALIMO); National Unity Party
(PUN); and United Democratic Front (UDF).
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Union has adopted Renamo's colours and flag, with
Dhlakama as its presidential candidate. It is believed that in
exchange Renamo has offered the minor parties seats on its
parliamentary lists in winnable positions, though this was not
specifically spelt out at Monday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
PRD leader Manecas Daniel becomes deputy president of the
coalition, and Maximo Dias, general secretary of MONAMO, is
chairman of the Electoral Union's General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the signing ceremony, Dias said that the
Electoral Union arises from the need to defeat the 24 years of
"political hegemony" imposed by the ruling Frelimo (Frente de
libertacao de Mocambique) party.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to put an end to this hegemony," he said,
adding that each party has sacrificed its individual political
interests with the aim of better serving the country.
</P>
<P>
The people are tired of Frelimo and it is time for it to
slacken its grip on power, Dhlakama said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
