<HEADLINE> Colombia Frees Exchange Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Colombia left its
closed-managed control of currency market and started a regime to
float peso freely from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Finance Minister Juan Camilo
Restrepo late Saturday in an extraordinary meeting of the
Directive Board of the Republic Bank, which had maintained the
country's exchange bank for 5 years and seven months.
</P>
<P>
Colombia is facing its worst economic crisis in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Colombia central bank sold more than 400 million dollars from
its international reserves in a bid to defend the peso from
speculative attack, and reserves were set to fall below the
psychological support level of 8 billion dollars. The peso had
devaluated twice in less than a year, which had undermined the
currency regime's credibility, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the peso closed at an all-time low of 1,994.29 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the peso could first fall to as much as 2,100 or
2,300 per dollar, but expected it to recover after a period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Develops Electronic Nose to Smell Out Infections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Researchers in Britain have
created an electronic nose which could dramatically cut diagnosis
time for infections by sniffing urine.
</P>
<P>
The device, called Diag-Nose and developed by Dr Selly Saini
and Dr Jan Leiferkus at Cranfield University, England, can also
identify the particular bacterium causing the infection, making
rapid treatment possible, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Urinary tract infections, such as thrush, are among the most
common adult infections needing medical attention.
</P>
<P>
Compared with currest diagnostic tests which are done in
laboratories and take up to 48 hours, the Diag-Nose can deliver
its diagnosis in a few hours and sit in a family doctor's
surgery.
</P>
<P>
The diagnosis begins with a small sample of urine being mixed
with a specially-developed growth fluid, which encourages the
micro-organisms to multiply and produce the tell-tale smells which
gives away their presence.
</P>
<P>
A syringe is then used to push a sample of the gas into the
electronic nose which identifies the particular aromas.
</P>
<P>
Initial trials of Diag-Nose have identified over 80 percent of
urinary tract infections. The researchers are planning clinical
trials to make a full evaluation of the device. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
