<HEADLINE> S. Africa Deplores Bus Crash killing 26 British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- South African Transport
Ministry Monday said it was devastated at the news of another bus
accident, which claimed the lives of 26 elderly British tourists.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three of the 38 passengers died at the scene when their
bus overturned on the Long Tom Pass between Lydenburg and Sabie in
Mpumalanga, about 300 kilometers east of Johannesburg at 12.20
p.m., police spokesman Gerrit Smit said.
</P>
<P>
He said that another three died shortly after they arrived at
Lydenburg hospital, with the rest 12 still in serious conditions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking from the scene of the accident, Smit said police were
at 3 p.m. still carrying away the bodies of the dead and gathering
up the tourists' luggage which was strewn all over the hillside.
</P>
<P>
The bus driver, who was not injured in the crash, told police
the brakes failed as he was driving down the pass and the bus
ended up lying on its side about 10 meters from the road, with its
top ripped off.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister Dullah Omar was shocked by the news and
immediately arranged a meeting with the country's bus operators
scheduled for Thursday, his spokesman Mike Mabasa said.
</P>
<P>
"The minister wants to see what precisely needs to be done to
bring down the high rate of accidents," Mabasa said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the British High Commission told South African
Press Association that the commission had yet to receive official
confirmation of the accident from the police, adding that the
consular staff in Pretoria were making enquiries.
</P>
<P>
Monday's crash was the fifth bus accident in a week, taking the
total death toll to 58 and more than 160 injured.
</P>
<P>
Hours before Monday's crash a bus driver appeared in the
Kokstad Magistrate's Court to face culpable homicide charges after
his bus crashed into a tree in mist at midnight on Friday, killing
14 people and injuring 30.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, six people died when two buses carrying
sports teams collided and one overturned near Bethlehem in Free
State.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, 12 people died when their bus crashed outside
Laingsburg in the Western Cape and on Thursday 35 people were
injured in a bus crash in Tarkastad in the Eastern Cape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
