<HEADLINE> Investment Levels Down In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Investment Center
(ZIC) Monday said it approved 65 projects worth more than 9.8
billion Zimbabwean dollars (257 million U.S. dollars) during the
first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Ncube, executive director of the ZIC, said that
although  the investment levels this year were lower than that of
last year, they were set to improve in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The commercial sector accounted for the largest slice of
approvals within the sectors at 5.1 billion Zimbabwean dollars
(134 million U.S. dollars) while mining was second at 1.8 billion
Zimbabwean dollars (47.3 million U.S. dollars) and the tourism
sector was third at 1.4 billion Zimbabwean dollars (36.8 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the total projects, the highest amount of five billion
Zimbabwean dollars (131.5 million U.S. dollars) was raised by
Britain and 2.7 billion Zimbabwean dollars (71 million U.S.
dollars) by South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ncube noted that his country was still failing to get direct
foreign investment because of the size of its market while
established markets in Nigeria and South Africa were capitalizing.
</P>
<P>
It did not mean that the country was not being effectively
marketed abroad, but that some things had to be put into
perspective first, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ncube said: "There are legal frameworks being worked out that
are meant to liberalize the communication sector and the
privatization process which will encourage more investment into
the country."
</P>
<P>
Last year ZIC approved more than 300 projects worth 60 billion
 Zimbabwean dollars (1.57 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
