<HEADLINE> Foreign Direct Investment in Africa Down: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment
(FDI) in Africa declined to about 8.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1998
from about 9.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, a senior United
Nations official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the newly released "World Investment Report 1999", Ali
Gadir Ali , economic and social policy division chief of the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said FDI flow
to developing countries decreased from about 174 billion U.S.
dollars in 1997 to about 166 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
None of the top 100 multinational corporations in the world is
from Africa, he said, adding that out of the 50 top multinational
corporations in the developing countries, only three are in Africa
-- in South Africa precisely.
</P>
<P>
Referring to FDI development in other parts of the world, Ali
said Asia also recorded a decline from 95.5 billion U.S. dollars
in 1997 to 84.9 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that China is an exception, adding that FDI
in China was constantly growing from 25.5 billion U.S. dollars in
1993 to 45.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ali attributed the steady increase of foreign investment in
China mainly to its government's economic reform. What is more
important, he said, China has become an expanding and major market
for transnational corporations.
</P>
<P>
"I think the wake of China in the world economy will qualify
her to receive more FDI as we go," Ali said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
