<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Ruling to Compensate Torture Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Monday
ruled that the Ministry of Interior compensate two alleged Muslim
Brotherhood members for tortures by police during the late
President Gamal Abdel Nasser's rule.
</P>
<P>
Under the unprecedented ruling, the ministry should give 30,000
Egyptian pounds (8,800 U.S. dollars) each to Mohammed Abdel Adhim
and Hassan Mohammed in compensation for physical and mental
tortures they claimed to have suffered when they were jailed in
1954-56, court officials said. Both men are now in their late
seventies.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time an Egyptian court has ordered such
redress for victims of torture who were political detainees during
Nasser's rule.
</P>
<P>
The court stated that its ruling was based on an international
agreement signed by Egypt in 1986 on the prevention of torture. It
said there is no time limit for defendants to seek redress in
torture cases.
</P>
<P>
Nasser banned the Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest Islamic
movement, after an alleged assassination attempt on him in
Alexandria in 1954. Thousands of group members were detained
without trial and many of its leaders were executed.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear if the Interior Ministry will appeal the ruling
and ministry officials could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
