<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, US Business Executives to Meet in Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Over 150 business executives
and government officials from the United States and the European
Union (EU) will hold "a brainstorming meeting" in Berlin to set
final stance on the agenda for the new round of talks within the
World Trade Organization, EU said in a newly published report.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen will meet at the fifth annual conference of the
Transatlantic Business Dialogue (TABD) to push for the new WTO
round to include a new Information Technology Agreement (ITA II),
an agreement on a permanent standstill on customs duties for
electronic transactions, and WTO support for a business-led
framework for electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
To be held exactly one month before the opening of the WTO's
key ministerial meeting in Seattle in which a new round of global
trade talks is due to be launched on November 30, the Berlin
meeting also aim for an agreement on accelerated tariff
liberalization (ATL), where possible, in agreed on sectors,
including ITA II, can be settled earlier than more complex
negotiations, the EU report said.
</P>
<P>
Other TABD priorities include an agreement on transparency in
government procurement, a standstill on tariffs on E-commerce, and
improved market access for the least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"The TABD wish-list backs the as-yet unshaped plans to
strengthen global investment rules through the WTO, as well as
continue to examine the interface between trade and environment
and trade and competition," the report said.
</P>
<P>
At the Berlin meeting, the business leaders and government
officials from Europe and the United States will call for a
strengthened dispute settlement mechanism, as well as
clarification of some of the WTO's ambiguous dispute settlement
articles, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FSA Publishes Policy Statement on Guidance and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) The Financial Services Authority
(the FSA) Monday publishes a Policy Statement about the use of its
powers to give guidance and waivers to financial firms under the
new Financial Services and Markets Bill.
</P>
<P>
The FSA aims to develop and sustain an open and responsive
two-way relationship with regulated firms and its approach to
guidance and waivers is being developed within this context.
</P>
<P>
The overall approach is to be responsive, helpful and
forthcoming while providing firms with the means to stand on their
own feet when working out how to meet regulatory standards and
requirements, according to the FSA.
</P>
<P>
The statement makes the following points on the three principal
areas covered -General Guidance, Individual Guidance and Waivers.
</P>
<P>
General guidance will be used to explain regulatory processes
and arrangements and to clarify the application of the new
legislation.
</P>
<P>
Individual Guidance is the one given to a particular firm or
person in relation to their own circumstances or plans.
</P>
<P>
And Waivers are dispensations which can be given to individual
firms in special circumstances. The effect of a waiver is to
change or disapply a rule applicable to the firm concerned.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Services and Markets Bill received its Second
Reading in the House of Commons on 28 June and is expected to
become law during the first half of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Thanks Voters for Expression of Free Will </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said on Monday he "appreciates the people's expression of
free will" in the referendum, something which "reflects the
Egyptians' keenness on having a say in decision-making."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak thanked the Egyptian people for exercising their
constitutional rights in a referendum on his presidency.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of Egypt's 24 million eligible voters cast
their ballots in the referendum on Sunday and Mubarak received
93.79 percent of "Yes" votes, securing a fourth six-year term.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential decree issued in the day, Mubarak called for
an extraordinary session of the parliament, the People's Assembly,
during which he is expected to be sworn in.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet reshuffle is also expected to be announced on the
occassion. .
</P>
<P>
He said he "followed closely the public outflow of feelings,"
which he termed as a reflection of "a deep understanding of the
future challenges."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader promised proper use of the national
resources for the people and called on the haves to translate
their feelings to deeds in backing the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was first elected president in 1981 after former
president Anwar Sadat was assassinated by Islamic radicals. He was
re-elected in 1987 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
During the past 18 years, Mubarak has pushed forward the peace
process with Israel and carried out a privatization program which
has helped Egypt maintain one of the best economic performances in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide televised speech on Friday, the 71-year-old
Mubarak promised to "broaden public participation" and "turn Egypt
into a modern society based on technology and science." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
