<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA President Urges Solidarity in Addressing Small  Islands' Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- President of the
United Nations General Assembly Theo-Ben Gurirab on Monday called
for unity and solidarity of the international community to address
the problems facing the small islands.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the special session of the General Assembly on small
islands, Gurirab said this is the last special session of the
General Assembly before the next millennium, and the small islands
states, the international community and future generations expect
from it a successful outcome from this timely and important
gathering.
</P>
<P>
Gurirab said the small island developing states had made
remarkable efforts to tackle their special ecological and economic
vulnerabilities and to put in place policies and measures to
implement the Program of Action adopted in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Many small island states today are facing the continued
deterioration of the marine environment and have to contend with
over-fishing, marine spills, dumping of ship-borne wastes in their
neighbourhoods, transport of nuclear and other toxic materials
through their territorial waters and watershed destabilization, "
the President said.
</P>
<P>
"A common hurdle faced by most small island developing nations
is the insufficiency of funds relative to the enormity of the
challenges at hand. External support has not been forthcoming on
the scale promised," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us reinvigorate the spirit of unity and solidarity, and
adhere with a purpose to the global partnership. If we join
forces, we can, must and will help open up new vistas for
development, prosperity and progress for the small island
developing states," the President added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
