<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Launches World's First Virtual Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A British animal park on
Monday launched what was billed as the world's first virtual zoo.
</P>
<P>
Net surfers can zoom in on www.howletts.net to see wild animals
roaming their enclosure at Howletts Wild Animal Park in southeast
England, the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
Six cameras enable Internet users to observe the world's
biggest captive gorilla colony, African elephants, Siberian tigers
and bongos, a species of African antelope.
</P>
<P>
"Howletts' crusade to preserve rare and endangered wildlife
attracts global recognition," the agency quoted Internet
entrepreneur Damian Aspinall, son of Howletts founder John
Aspinall, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We want people around the world to see the animals' excellent
conditions in real time and learn about our unique breeding
achievements. No other animal park or zoo can match this virtual
live experience," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of U.S. World War II Pilots Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A US expert team left Guilin
for home today with the remains of American airmen from a B-24
bomber which crashed into a mountain in southern China during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
So far, after three years of joint exploration, the remains of
all ten airmen who died when their B-24 crashed during a return
flight to Guangxi after a bombing mission against Japanese ships
near Taiwan on Aug. 31, 1944, have been repatriated to their
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the bomber was first found in October 1996 by
two local peasants, and the finding aroused immediate attention
from the two governments.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin informed President Bill Clinton about the
discovery at the APEC leadership meeting in November 1996, and
presented him with the five identification cards found and a video
tape about the site of the crash.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, Defense Minister Chi Haotian visited the US
and handed over part of the discovery to his US counterpart
William Perry.
</P>
<P>
The joint research work formally started in January 1997, and
altogether four research actions were carried out before the
complete handover.
</P>
<P>
The rough terrain of the Mao'er mountain where the bomber
crashed made this a tough task. In the first search in 1997, a
female journalist from the Voice of America slipped over a cliff,
and it took a rescue team of more than ten Chinese over four hours
to finally rescue her.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, more than 1,000 Chinese people were
involved during these operations over three years, and lasted
until it was called a complete success by both sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
