<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papandreou: Athens Will Start Dialogue With Turkey on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou said Monday that Greece would be prepared to start
dialogue with neighboring Turkey on the remaining "high-impact"
issues if the two countries could sign cooperation agreements on
the "low-impact" issues such as tourism, trade and culture.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Athens daily "Ta Nea", Papandreou said
that the recent improvement of the climate in Greek-Turkish
relations could not have negative efforts on the Cyprus issue,
while the expansion of the "low-impact" Greek-Turkish dialogue to
other secondary issues in no way meant that Greece had shelved the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Cyprus government also regarded the recent
Greek-Turkish rapprochement as particularly positive.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the present conjuncture was unique for
enabling progress in the Cyprus problem and the U.S. would move
actively in that direction.
</P>
<P>
As for Turkey's accession to the European Union (EU),
Papandreou said that Turkey's future EU membership would be in
Greece's long-term interests, but Greece's position at December's
EU summit hinged on Turkey's attitude on Greek-Turkish affairs and
the Cyprus issue and on the Guarantees Greece would secure from
the EU on its national interests.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have
been strained for decades over their disputes in the territorial
waters, air space limits, the delimitation of the continental
shelf in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the two neighbors, which have nearly gone to
war three times in the past 25 years, have been trying hard to
improve their relations with the start of low-level talks between
senior Greek- Turkish foreign ministry officials, but they have
not touched the sensitive issues such as territorial disputes and
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The earthquakes in Turkey and Greece also provided an
opportunity for both sides to show their willingness to better
bilateral time. Rescue crews from Greece and Turkey have fought
side-by-side in pulling earthquake survivors out of the rubble of
the collapsed buildings in both countries.
</P>
<P>
The progress made in the talks and the good feeling generated
by mutual help over the earthquake tragedies are hoped to pave the
way for both sides to eventually better their bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Expand State-run TV and Radio Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia plans to expand
the coverage of state-run television and radio in the whole
country to reduce the damage of Khmer culture by the foreign
programs.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Information Lu Laysreng, the
government would spend about one million U.S. dollars over the
next year to ensure that all areas get Cambodian broadcasting.
Only 28 percent of the country can get Cambodian broadcasting at
present.
</P>
<P>
Foreign televisions now cover the whole country, the minister
said, "the government wants rural people to get their programs
through our broadcasting."
</P>
<P>
The people in northern and western Cambodia get television and
radio broadcasts from Thailand while the people in central and
eastern areas pick up Vietnamese channels.
</P>
<P>
In addition, cable televisions and satellite televisions make
foreign TV and radio programs easy available since cable and
satellite dishes are inexpensive these days.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia now has six television stations, but even the
state-run TVK can not cover the whole country without tapes being
sent to the provincial broadcasting stations.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia has struggled to rebuild its culture and tradition
from the devastation of the decades of civil war. Earlier this
year, the minister issued a 13-point order, urging the television
and radio stations to "use dignified language and avoid foreign
words" and to play Cambodian-made programs.
</P>
<P>
Pornographic and violent films are banned in Cambodia, any
program that encourages children to smoke or drink alcohol is also
banned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
