<HEADLINE> 2 Lebanese Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A member of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) and a guerrilla of the anti-Israeli
military group Hezbollah were killed in south Lebanon on Monday,
Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi Saghir, chief of SLA's outpost at Beit Yahoun, where is a
crossing point in the Israeli occupied border zone in south
Lebanon, was killed when his car was blown up by a bomb on the
village's road.
</P>
<P>
Three other SLA militiamen and a school teacher were also
injured in the blast.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack, adding one of its fighters was
killed Monday in fire exchange with Israeli forces inside the
border enclave.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes bombed a number of villages and wadies in
and around the zone to revenge the casualty its SLA ally had
suffered in the day.
</P>
<P>
The fresh fatality raised to 17 the number of SLA members
killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year while 13
Israeli soldiers lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli troops and SLA out of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
