<HEADLINE> Second Singapore Navy Ship Sets Sail for Darwin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The second of the two navy
ships committed to the peacekeeping mission to East Timor set sail
Monday for Darwin, Australia, Singapore Ministry of Defense
announced.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister of State for Defense David Lim, who is also
the minister of state for information and the arts, officiated
Monday at the sending-off ceremony for RSS Intrepid, the second
Singapore Landing Ship Tank (LST) to join the International Force
for East Timor (INTERFET) at Tuas Naval Base, the ministry said in
a press release.
</P>
<P>
Lim addressed the crew of 86 officers and men and handed the
sea ensign to the LST's Commanding Officer Major David Lau, the
ministry added,
</P>
<P>
RSS Intrepid is scheduled to arrive in Darwin on October 6,
1999, and will join the first LST, RSS Excellence, which departed
on September 18 and is to arrive in Darwin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
LSTs, the largest ships in Singapore's navy's fleet, are used as
a transport and training platform and will provide logistics
support for INTERFET.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's mission to East Timor involves about 250 Singapore
Armed Services personnel and its contribution of military
personnel comprises a small number of military observers and a
medical detachment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
