<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Mowlam Says N.Irish Peace Process Still Working </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 27 (Xinhua) -- British
Secretary for Northern Ireland Mo Mowlam said on Monday that the
peace process in the province is still working.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Labour Party's annual conference, Mowlam said
"the process is succeeding, but there is still a long way to go."
</P>
<P>
She admitted that none of the democratic bodies set out in the
Good Friday Agreement are working properly, as "there's no
executive, no Ministers, no North/South Council, no Council of the
Isles."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, she added, none of the major paramilitary
organizations has been dismantled, nor has the process of
decommissioning begun in any meaningful way.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fact that attitudes are changing, the two sides
simply do not trust each other enough," she said. "There is a
gulf of distrust between them that neither side will deliver
because they can't believe the other will respond."
</P>
<P>
The British and Irish Governments have tried and were very
close to success, but they "can't make it happen," she said. "The
will has to be there on the part of the political leaders
themselves if this is going to work."
</P>
<P>
George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator who chaired the peace
process last year, is holding a formal review of the Agreement,
but he "hasn't got a magic wand," she said, adding that "change is
difficult for people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
