<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Cut 1,800 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT),
the country's central bank, is undergoing a five-year
restructuring program, reducing the stuff members by 1,800, the
bank's governor Chatumongkol Sonakul said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that the program, to be started this week,
aims to increase efficiency and accountability of the bank.
</P>
<P>
The program would involve in reducing the management layers
from six to two, leading to an expected total of 1,800 staff, from
currently 6,000, having to leave the agency at the end of the
five-year program.
</P>
<P>
A maximum 400 staff will have to leave the bank in the first
year of the re-organization program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongkul hoped to form a management layer comprising the
governor, deputy governors and assistant governors, with 25 units
operating directly and indirectly in a non-hierarchical structure.
</P>
<P>
The new structure divides the central bank's tasks into five
areas, including monetary policy, financial institution
supervision, administration, financial institution rehabilitation
and planning.
</P>
<P>
A 600-million-baht (15-million-U.S. dollar) budget will be set
aside for mutual separation program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
