<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Climate Change to Impact U.S. Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Climate change is likely
to impact both the availability and quality of the U.S. water
supply, according to a new study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The study, sponsored by the Pew Center, an environmental
organization, finds that as climate change alters precipitation,
evapotranspiration and runoff in the United States, these changes
are likely to affect the magnitude, frequency and costs of extreme
weather events as well as the nation's water supply.
</P>
<P>
As one of consistent impacts identified by the study, higher
temperatures in mountainous watersheds will increase the ratio of
rain to snow, accelerate the rate of spring snowmelt and shorten
the overall snowfall season, leading to more rapid, earlier and
greater spring runoff.
</P>
<P>
In already arid regions, there is likely to be greater flux in
the water supply, while higher temperatures fuel an increased
demand for water. In other areas, new instances of flooding and
droughts also will impact the availability of water.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, while higher water flows could improve
water quality in some streams, the increased runoff of pollutants
and saltwater intrusion could accompany climate change induced
sea-level rise.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the most important step to take today is to reduce
the greenhouse gas omissions that cause climate change, the study
suggests opportunities to develop water marketing and trading
strategies and improve the management of water systems. Other
steps include expanding the existing infrastructure such as
reservoirs and dams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes 6,000 U.N. Troops for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday recommended the establishment of a 6,000-strong
U.N. peacekeeping force to help implement a July accord aimed at
ending an eight-year civil war in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on the U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra
Leone (UNOMSIL), Annan said that he hoped the force would be able
to incorporate a substantial number of troops from the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), whose own 12,000-member
Nigerian-led military observer group called ECOMOG is being phased
out after serving in Sierra Leone for two and half years.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo has agreed
to his proposal to deploy a U.N. peacekeeping force which would
include some Nigerian and other troops in the proposed force for
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The July 7 agreement was signed in Lome, capital of Togo, by
Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Kabbah and Corporal Foday Sankoh,
head of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of Nigerian troops, who make up the bulk of
ECOMOG, began on August 31, but was suspended following a
meeting between the Nigerian and Sierra Leonean presidents,
Annans said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his report that, without security, it would not
be possible to carry out a program of disarming and demobilizing
some 45,000 ex-combatants, many of them children, and thus remove
a threat to the West African country's stability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N. chief also called for the immediate return
to Sierra Leone of Sankoh, to "assure important functions within
the government of Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the commitment of Sankoh and his senior
associates, including Johnny Paul Koroma, leader of the Armed
Forces Revolutionary Council, to the Lome agreement was an
essential element in its effective implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
