<HEADLINE> Uganda's Referendum to Be Held in June Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's coming referendum,
which will decide the country's future system of governance, will
be held during June 2-16 of 2000, Aziz Kasujia, chairman of the
Electoral Commission, announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This follows the dismissal by the Constitutional Court of the
petition by some MPs in opposition parties, Kasujia said at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Kasujia said that the exact date for referendum will be further
fixed, adding that the result will be respected regardless of the
turnout at the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda Constitution, enacted in 1995, provides that a
referendum will be held in five years to decide the country's
political system by its people. The Referendum Act states that the
date of the coming vote should be between June 3 to July 2 of the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Opposition headed by the Democratic Party has argued that
general elections, instead of a referendum, should be held next
year because at the referendum the ruling National Resistance
Movement (NRM) and other parties will not be competing on the same
footing.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni has stated on several
occasions that the referendum is contained in the constitution and
therefore any opposition to the referendum should be regarded as
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Though confronted with much resistance from multipartists, it
is widely believed that the referendum will be held in time and
the ruling NRM is expected to win.  
</P>
</TEXT>
