<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmakers Call on Congress to Pay U.N. Arrears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Republican and
Democratic lawmakers came to the United Nations headquarters in
New York to demand the U.S. Congress pay the nation's some 1.7
billion U.S. dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
"It's outrageous and embarrassing that the United States -- the
wealthiest country in the world -- is the biggest deadbeat at the
U.N.," said Rep. Nita Lowery, a Democrat from New York.
</P>
<P>
She was joined at a press conference by Chris Shays, a
Republican from Conn., and Eliot Engel, a Democrat from New York,
to draw attention to the debt and release a letter to the
congressional leadership demanding the dues be paid.
</P>
<P>
The letter, to House Speaker Dennis Hastert and House Minority
leader Richard Gephardt, warned that U.S. foreign policy was being
undermined by the arrears.
</P>
<P>
The United States is again threatened this year with its vote
at the General Assembly if it doesn't pay an estimated 350 million
U.S. dollars by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Congress has held up to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars for years,
demanding the United States streamline its organization and
institute a no-growth budget. Legislation that would have paid off
the bulk of the bills was vetoed last year by U.S. President Bill
Clinton because it contained unrelated restrictions on U.S.
spending for overseas family planning organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Those who insist on linking these two issues now hold U.N.
arrears funding hostages," Lowery said. "As this nonsense
continues, these opportunities squander the successes we have
gained through out participation in the U.N." 
</P>
</TEXT>
