<HEADLINE> S. Africa Proposes Popular Elections for Resolving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki said here Monday that free and fair elections could
contribute to the settlement of African conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the South African Development Community (SADC)
Electoral Commissions Forum in the Tanzanian capital, Mbeki said
many powerful persons in Africa "abused their power to gain undue
wealth and advantage for themselves, their relatives and friends
by illegal or immoral means".
</P>
<P>
These persons in power consider "the enhancement of
transparency, accountability and accessibility" as the enemies of
"good governance", said Mbeki, who arrived in Tanzania Sunday on a
two-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
He said in the past Ghana was a victim to a succession of
military coups, but "since Ghana returned to democratic rule there
has been no further recurrence of these coups".
</P>
<P>
"I'm certain that all of us would agree that any democratic
settlement in countries such as Rwanda, Burundi and Sudan, to
mention only some, would require that special constitutional and
political measures are introduced to ensure both majority rule and
the protection of national minorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "we have to grapple correctly with the issues
of the ethnic, linguistic, religious and other diversity of our
societies".
</P>
<P>
"Regular elections must be held," he said. "Preferably, these
elections should be managed by independent electoral commissions."
</P>
<P>
"The regular exercise by the citizens to participate in free
and fair elections indeed constitutes one of the basic guarantees
of regional peace and stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
The annual forum, the first of its kind, brings together
representatives of electoral offices or commissions from 14 SADC
member countries.
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-day forum, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
said people in southern African can and must work together to
create an even large and more prosperous home through free, fair,
transparent and periodic elections.
</P>
<P>
The forum was set up in Cape Town, South Africa, on July 27,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his visit to Tanzania Monday, Mbeki told
reporters that he had discussed with Mkapa on how to strengthen
economic co-operation.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit to Tanzania by Mbeki who came to power
last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
