<HEADLINE> Ghana Registers 1.3 billion-U.S. Dollar Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ghana Investment
Promotion Centre (GIPC) registered 780 projects involving an
estimated capital of 1.3 billion U.S. dollars between 1994 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
About 78 percent of the projects, involving over 997 million
U.S. dollars, are in foreign equity and loans, according to the
World Investment Report launched under the theme "Foreign Direct
Investment and the Challenge of Development" in the Ghanaian
capital Accra Monday.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 780 projects, 534 (over 68 percent) were registered
as joint venture projects and 246 (31.54 percent) were wholly
foreign-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, Ghana's Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) declined to 45
million U.S. dollars last year from 82 million U.S. dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
It was the second successive decline compared to the 120
million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Gyasi, director of GIPC Research and Development,
acknowledged that Ghana has to strengthen its efforts to enable it
to become a strong investment location.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain has been the major source of FDI into the
country with 81 projects. China follows with 59 projects and the
United States with 58 projects.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, innovative and proactive measures for sourcing
investments into Ghana need to be undertaken," Gyasi said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not only to sustain Ghana as a competitive investment
location, but to enhance the business environment, particularly in
reducing establishment cost and time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Gyasi said the GIPC is reviewing the legal framework for
investment and shifting its promotion from a general to a more
targeted approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
