<HEADLINE> German Doctors Revive Man Whose Heart Stopped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A man whose heart stopped
beating for sever hours was revived by heroic efforts of a team of
German doctors, according to a report published in the current
issue of British medical journal The Lancet.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year old man in Berlin, Germany, believed to have eaten
toxic berries, was found comatose in a park and was taken to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Doctors then tried electric shocks, heart-stimulating drugs and
a pacemaker. They kept his circulation going, maintaining oxygen
to the brain by constant external massage of his heart.
</P>
<P>
After seven hours, a normal heart rhythm was restored and the
man gradually regained consciousness.
</P>
<P>
The incident raised questions over whether enough effort was
made to resuscitate young, otherwise fit patients suffering
cardiac arrest, said the chief author Professor Friederich Luft,
from the Franz Volhard Clinic of the Humboldt University of
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
"I have worked in the U.S. and I am sure they would have given
up there after one and a half hours," he says, "In this case, the
German team was very good physicians and they wouldn't give up.
They saved his life."
</P>
<P>
"In an 80-year-old with heart disease it would be a different
matter, but in a younger person with a cardiac arrest of unknown
cause you shouldn't give up. This is the message." he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
