<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two German Energy Giants Begin Merger Steps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- In the largest case of corporate
fusion in Germany this year, Veba and Viag, both giants in the
energy branch, Monday began their steps of tying up to the largest
energy supplier in the world.
</P>
<P>
This message was announced in Duesseldorf and Munich,
respective headquarters of the two firms in the early morning
after the supervisory board of Viag approved the merger plan
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Duesseldorf-based Veba AG and the Viag AG, based in Munich,
together have an annual turnover of 150 billion marks (80 billion
U.S. dollars) and a staff of 200,000. The new company after merger
will become the third largest German industrial concern after
Daimler-Chrysler and Siemens.
</P>
<P>
"In the energy branch where there is a pressure of becoming
giant, this fusion is only the first step," said Ulrich Hartmann,
chairman of Veba, at a press conference in Munich. He added that
the ultimate goal of the new concern was to become a world player.
</P>
<P>
The new company, the name of which to be decided in October,
will have its headquarters in Duesseldorf and be co-led by
Hartmann and his counterpart in Viag, Wihelm Simson.
</P>
<P>
Two main areas of the new concern, chemicals and power supply,
will be launched on January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, the power supply units of Viag and Veba,
respectively Bayernwerk and Preussen Elektra, will tie up to a new
energy group based in Munich.
</P>
<P>
Other major units of Veba and Viag will be merged in the next
two or three years, Hartmann said, adding, "We will not let
ourselves in a rush."
</P>
<P>
According to the merger plan, shareholding in the new concern
will be weighed at a ratio of 67 percent for Veba and 33 percent
for Viag. And Viag shareholders will receive one Veba share per
2.8 Viag shares.
</P>
<P>
Hartmann and Simson expected the approval of the Federal Cartel
Office, Germany's anti-trust watchdog. And in next February, the
merger plan will be passed by major shareholder sessions of the
two companies.
</P>
<P>
Besides energy supply and chemicals, the new concern will also
operate in the fields of telecommunication and real estate. Other
operations, including packaging, logistics, trading and aluminum
refining, will possibly be divested off step by step, Hartmann
said.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, those units to be sold will account for 55 billion
marks (30 billion U.S. dollars) and a work force of almost
100,000.
</P>
<P>
The way for the merger was cleared after the Bavarian state
government decided to back the plan and sell 10 percent of its
stake in Viag to Veba for 3.1 billion marks. By now, the Bavarian
government holds 25.1 percent of the Viag stake.
</P>
<P>
Bavarian state premier Edmund Stoiber called the merger plan
"by far the most attractive solution for Viag and for Bavaria."
</P>
<P>
Energy supply, chemicals and telecommunication, all covered by
Viag, are three most important industrial fields of Bavaria, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"If Bayernwerk (the power supply unit of Viag) had remained
alone, sooner or later it would become a takeover target with
unforeseeable consequences for the company and for the jobs in
Bavaria," said Stoiber.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say two main reasons for the merger are the fierce
competition in a liberalized German domestic energy market, and,
more important, the tougher pressure facing German companies in
the European and world stage since the European common currency
has been launched.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the merger, the two companies will save at least
1.6 billion marks annually by 2002. And about 2,500 jobs, chiefly
in the energy unit, will be cut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
