<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDI Flows to Africa Drop: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Direct Investment
(FDI) in Africa accounted for only four percent of the total for
the developing countries, down from nine percent in 1989, a
United Nations report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Africa benefited from a rise in FDI inflows since the early
1990s, but the growth in FDI flows to the region was much less
than that in FDI flows to other developing countries, leaving much
of Africa's potential for FDI unutilized," said the newly released
World Investment Report 1999 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the reforms that have taken place and the progress
expected in a number of African countries in terms of improving
the business environment,
</P>
<P>
further work is needed to change the image of the continent,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Africa attracted 8.3 billion U.S. dollars of foreign direct
investment (FDI) in 1998, about 12 percent less than that in the
previous year, according to the report sponsored by the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
The decrease was largely due to a dramatic drop in FDI flows to
South Africa, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
South Africa witnessed an unprecedented peak in terms of
privatization- related FDI inflows in 1997 but a drop in 1998 to
levels of previous years, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rest of the continent registered a moderate
increase, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by UNCTAD shows that the leading industries
that attracted FDI were telecommunications, food, beverages,
tourism, textiles and clothing as well as mining and quarrying
during the 1996-1998 period.
</P>
<P>
Between 2000 and 2003, they are expected to be tourism, food
and beverages, telecommunications as well as textile and leather,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The five countries ranked most attractive to foreign investors
in Africa for the period 2000-2003 are South Africa, Nigeria,
Botswana, Cote d' Ivoire and Tunisia, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
