<HEADLINE> Ghana, U.S. Sign US$5.3 Million Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and the United States
Monday signed an agreement on providing the west African country
with 5.3 million U.S. dollars in the form of a grant , Ghana News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This brings the total amount of U.S. government assistance to
Ghana to 68 million dollars for the fiscal year ending September
30.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Finance Victor Selormey signed for Ghana
while Director of the United States Agency for International
Development (USAID) Frank Young initialled for his country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 850,000 dollars of the amount will be used
for supporting the export sector while another one million dollars
will go to the health sector to help improve family planning and
child health care.
</P>
<P>
Out of the amount, 2.5 million dollars will be used for
improving communications through Internet connectivity for
educational and civic institutions while another one million
dollars be used to acquire logistics for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest aid level the United States has given to
Ghana since 1992, Young said.

