<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Exports Continue to Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total exports
continued to pick up in August 1999, according to external trade
figures released today by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports (comprising re-exports and domestic
exports) in August 1999 increased by 4.4 percent over a year
earlier to 124.3 billion HK dollars (15.93 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within this total, the value of re-exports rose by 6.7 percent
to 108.5 billion HK dollars (13.91 billion U.S. dollars), while
that of domestic exports decreased by 9.5 percent to 15.9 billion
HK dollars (2.03 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, the value of imports in August 1999 increased by
1.7 percent over a year earlier to 121.9 billion HK dollars (15.62
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade surplus of 2.4 billion HK dollars (307.6
million U.S. dollars), equivalent to 2.0 percent of the value of
imports, was recorded in August 1999, in contrast to the deficit
of 0.7 billion HK dollars (89.7 million U.S. dollars), equivalent
to 0.6 percent of the value of imports, recorded in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that the further pick-
up in Hong Kong's total exports in August was mainly led by the
strong recovery in demand in East Asia and sustained robust demand
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Exports to China's mainland should have also arrested its
downtrend since April 1998, in line with the distinct rebound in
the mainland's exports lately.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that with the further improvement in
exports alongside the still modest absorption of imports, Hong
Kong's visible trade account attained a surplus in August 1999 for
the first time since January 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
