<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outgoing British Defense Secretary on European Defense Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing British
Secretary for Defense George Robertson, who has been appointed the
next secretary-general of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
Tuesday defined the European Defense Initiative as a program to "
meet tomorrow's threats, not yesterday's enemies."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the need for "nations of Europe to have the right
armed forces to fight and win," Robertson told the Labor Party's
annual conference that "forces to meet tomorrow's threats, not
yesterday's enemies, are what the new European Defense Initiative
is all about."
</P>
<P>
He expounded on the importance of "getting the troops to the
crisis, in the right time, with the right training, the right
equipment and the ability to supply and protect themselves,"
saying: "It is urgent that we do it and that the Europeans do it
together."
</P>
<P>
Britain has led the way in this regard, as the country's
Strategic Defense Review is seen as the most radical modernization
of Britain's defenses in a generation, said Robertson.
</P>
<P>
But responding to crises as they happen is not enough, he said.
"We must do all we can to prevent these conflicts from happening
in the first place."
</P>
<P>
That is why that for the first time in British history, the
Labor Government has transformed conflict prevention and defense
diplomacy from a secondary task for British forces to one of their
primary missions, he said.
</P>
<P>
After an account of the Government's defense endeavors in the
past year and more, Robertson said "Britain is back where it
should be -- leading in Europe and leading in the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese Enterprises Eye World Market (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his view, a criterion for the world's most competitive
company should be evaluated in terms of assets, market share,
creative ability, management skills, business turnover and
development potential.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the 200 Chinese enterprises participating in
the current Fortune Forum regard the occasion as a good chance for
them to enter the world market.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Xinxian, president of Shenzhen-based Sanjiu Group, pledged
that he will turn his group into the world's largest and most
advanced herbal pharmaceutical plant in five years.
</P>
<P>
And Huayuan Group said it will take the advantage of the
government's new policies on trade expansion for enterprises to
build 10 production bases and 20 trade companies overseas in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, China has established 5,666
overseas enterprises with a combined investment of 6.32 billion U.
S. dollars from the Chinese side. These cover a wide range
including trade, manufacturing, resources development, processing,
transport, medicine and tourism. Non-trade firms constitute 40
percent of the total. The most active sectors include household
electric appliances, tourism, telecommunications, and textiles.
</P>
<P>
At present, 30 of the 225 largest global contractors in the
world are Chinese, with a total workforce of 300,000.
</P>
<P>
Chinese entrepreneurs all hold the view that more Chinese firms
will be added to the list of the top 500 when the country's
overall economic strength is improved, though many enterprises
still lack experience and brand-name recognition at the present
stage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
