<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Promotes Active Europe Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, September 28 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook told the Labor Party in the Party's annual conference
on Tuesday that "Britain is leading Europe" as a result of the
Party's efforts to have Britain's voice heard in and out of Europe.
</P>
<P>
Contrasting what he called Labor's "new internationalism" to
the Conservative Party's "isolationism", Cook said that "under
Labor, Britain is leading Europe, not leaving Europe."
</P>
<P>
Britain is leading the reform of Europe, making it more open,
more in touch with people, he said, adding "but Britain will not
be taken seriously on the case of reform, if Europe does not
believe we want to make it a success."
</P>
<P>
It will be a disaster for Britain to be withdrawn from Europe,
because Britain sells most of its exports to Europe and Britain
needs to be there when rules are drawn up in Europe, he said. "
Because we and our neighbors face the same problems of cross-
border crime, the same challenges of protecting our environment,
and we need common solutions. Besides, we need the united
strength of Europe when we talk to the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
If it becomes clear that the "five tests" are met and that
Britain's interests would be better served by joining the Single
Currency, the Labor Government will invite the British people in a
referendum to make the right choice, Cook said. "If the economic
conditions are right, Labor will not let Britain lose out by
staying out."
</P>
<P>
For many British people, out of Europe would mean out of work,
he said. "Isolation in the modern world carries a big penalty in
the global economy."
</P>
<P>
"We recognize globalization demands a New Internationalism," he
said. "And our internationalism recognizes that we cannot deliver
our domestic program working alone in the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
