<HEADLINE> HK Spectators to Enjoy Spectacular Performances on National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 40,000 Hong Kong
spectators will be treated to a two-hour extravaganza which will
feature some unique public performances to celebrate the Golden
Jubilee of the People's Republic of China at Hong Kong Stadium on
October 1 (Friday) starting at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the evening promises to be military drills by
the People's Liberation Army Forces based in Hong Kong at an
unprecedented scale outside of China's mainland. It will perform,
among other things, the bayonet group calisthenics which will
highlight the soldiers' bearing, discipline and coordinated
movements, the Chinese Boxing group calisthenics which will show
their martial arts skill, and feature a military band which will
display calisthenics patterns as it plays its music.
</P>
<P>
Local talents that will be featured include a 500-strong dance
team formed by the Hong Kong Dance Federation from 12 secondary
schools. It will present a unique musical entitled "Dance of Youth
", which incorporates traditional characteristics of oriental and
western dances as well as social features unique to Hong Kong.
This will be the first such musical of its kind originating from
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the same vein, the Hong Kong Wushu Union team will feature
one big dragon, four smaller dragons and 50 lions. The dragons
will form themselves into the number "50" to symbolize the Golden
Jubilee as the lions dance around it and team members perform
their Kung Fu routines in their performance appropriately named "
Show of Vim and Vigor".
</P>
<P>
The rousing finale, called "Joy to the New Millennium", will
comprise a grand musical involving some of the best known local
artists, including Kelly Chen, Sammi Cheng, Andy Hui, Andy Lau,
Alan Tam and Faye Wong. They will be backed up by uniformed youth
groups who will perform marches, as well as lion and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 2,500 youths will team up to present a flip board
display showing the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
emblem and the logo of the 50th Anniversary of the National Day.
</P>
<P>
The extravaganza will be officiated by the Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa after representative teams of all disciplined services of
the HKSAR Government have marched into the stadium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
