<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest Against Japanese Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people from all walks
of life and some friendly Japanese protested recently in Harbin,
capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, over the
ruling by a Tokyo District Court on September 22 that the Japanese
government is not responsible for compensating 10 Chinese
plaintiffs, victims and surviving family members of Japanese
atrocities during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Japan inflicted tremendous sufferings on the Chinese people
during the war, but the court did not acknowledge the right of
foreign individuals to seek compensation for war damages from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The ruling is regarded as unjust and extremely absurd, as it
tramples on international law and has deeply hurt the feelings of
the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The protesters will continue supporting the plaintiffs in their
appeal to a higher court in Japan until the victims get their
deserved compensation.
</P>
<P>
During the war, Japanese military unit 731, based in Harbin,
conducted biological experiments using bubonic plague, anthrax and
cholera on thousands of Chinese prisoners of war and civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
