<HEADLINE> France Calls for Political Solution to Conflict in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- France called on Russia on
Tuesday to seek a political solution to the conflict in Chechnya,
and expressed concern about the influx of refugees into the
neighbors of the Caucasus republic.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that a political solution can be put to work in the
spirit of dialogue and the agreement of 1996," said French Foreign
Ministry assistant spokesman Francois Rivasseau.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the agreement reached by General Alexander
Lebed and the Chechen rebels on the withdrawal of Russian troops
putting an end to 21 months of war starting from 1994.
</P>
<P>
Lebed was then the presidential security advisor of Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Today we are worried by the escalation of the military
operations (by Russia) in Chechnya and by the influx of refugees
in the neighboring republics," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Russian troops have been intensifying their bombings against
targets in Chechnya for six days, killing hundreds of people, most
of them civilians.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has called on Moscow to use force against
the Islamic rebels in the Caucasus in a "restrained way." 
</P>
