<HEADLINE> Lesotho to Launch Food Relief Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government
will launch an emergency food relief program to help families
hardest hit by the present drought, South African Press
Association reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A minister in the prime minister's office, Sephiri Motanyane,
was quoted as saying that 280,000 villagers in all the
constituencies would be provided with food relief.
</P>
<P>
The government bought 20,000 tons of maize, which would be
distributed under a food-for-work scheme.
</P>
<P>
Motanyane said the food-for-work scheme would involve
agricultural production, road construction and implementation of
soil conservation measures such as the building of dams. These
projects, aimed at developing affected areas, would ensure that
people did not receive handouts of free food.
</P>
<P>
Participants would each receive 50 kilograms of maize over a
10-day working period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
