<HEADLINE> France Releases Mauritanian Officer Accused of Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A French court released on
Tuesday a Mauritanian army officer who was detained in July for
suspected crimes of torture in his own country, Agence France-
Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
The Chamber of Accusation of the Appeal Court of Montpellier,
southwest France, released Captain Ely Ould Dah, who was accused
of torturing two Mauritanian officers in 1991 suspected of joining
a coup plot against President Maaouya Ould Taya one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The officer was studying as an infantry intern in France, when
he was arrested on July 2 after being accused by two human rights
groups in France.
</P>
<P>
His arrest caused a diplomatic crisis between France and
Mauritania, which expelled all French military advisors and
recalled Mauritanian students from France.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyer of case, Luc Abratkieuwicz, said that the arrest
has caused trouble to "national and international public order
with its racist character."
</P>
<P>
The court said that Ould Dah could resume his study in the
School of Application of Infantry of Montpellier but cannot travel
out of the region of Herault in southwest France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
