<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Tourist Industry to Develop With Renewed Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's tourist
industry has experienced a year-on-year growth for 14 consecutive
months since the second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The post-handover downturn was reversed during the second half
of 1998, and double-digit growth was recorded for the first
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
This was said here today by Chairman of the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA) Lo Yuk Sui during its 41st annual general
meeting being held at the Furama Hotel, in Central, Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the HKTA's 1998/9 Annual Report, Lo said that until
recently, Hong Kong was blessed by a conjunction of three positive
factors: global interest in Hong Kong, booming regional prosperity
and a highly favorable demand-supply situation.
</P>
<P>
But, after the handover, there had been a temporary downturn in
Hong Kong's tourist industry. Total visitor arrivals for 1998 was
9.57 million, down eight percent on 1997's 10.41 million, while
total tourism receipts fell 23.4 percent to 55.3 billion HK
dollars (7.08 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lo noted, however, that the temporary downturn was in many ways
a blessing in disguise. It has helped the HKTA and the industry at
large to focus on the medium- and long-term needs of visitors.
Sophisticated market research was being used to better identify
those needs to ensure that Hong Kong maintains a sustainable
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
The key objective for the association for the coming year would
be the pursuit of higher yields and increased earnings, the
chairman said. "The major message gleaned from the past year is
that to remain competitive in the new millennium, the industry
must strengthen the perception of Hong Kong as being a destination
that offers better value for money. This is an image that must be
expanded and polished over the coming year through the provision
of quality services," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Through such initiatives as the newly established Heritage
Tourism Task Force and the cultural tourism round table we are
ensuring that we are developing attractions to meet consumer
demand," the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
"Overseas, our strategic directions and marketing efforts are
being geared to the needs of the individual markets. We can no
longer rely on being a destination whose reputation rests only on
food, shopping and hotels," he said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman also noted that in the coming year, the HKTA will
strengthen its relationships with China's mainland and other Asian
destinations in order to develop multi-destination itineraries and
capitalize on Hong Kong's hub position and status as the preferred
gateway to Asia and China. The association will also be utilizing
new media options -- such as the Internet -- for communications,
sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
HKTA Executive Director Amy Chan, Commissioner for Tourism Mike
Rowse and other members of the Board of Management also attended
the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
