<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Airbus Company, a European
consortium, will train Iraqi pilots, engineers and technicians on
the most sophisticated planes of the company outside Iraq on its
own account.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) on Tuesday quoted Nicolas Girop, Airbus'
regional sales director in the Middle East, as saying the training
will be in Jordan or perhaps in some other countries.
</P>
<P>
Nicolas, who visited Baghdad on Sunday and Monday with an
Airbus delegation, held talks with Iraqi Transport Minister Ahmed
Murtada Ahmed. During the talks, the Airbus official renewed the
commitment to implementing deals signed with Iraq once the
U.N. sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
According to a contract Airbus company signed with Iraq before
U.N. sanctions were imposed in 1990 following Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait, Airbus will supply five planes to the Iraqi Airways.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Airways has been grounded since the U.N. air embargo on
Iraq, part of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Iraqi Airways Rabee Mohammed Saleh told
INA that his company has started selecting pilots, engineers and
technicians who will receive training next month. 
