<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Leaders to Sign Pact on Charter-change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada will sign with leaders of Congress this week a tripartite
covenant binding lawmakers to take up only proposed economic
reforms to the 1987 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said Tuesday in a statement that this pact would be the
strongest proof yet that he wants only economic reforms to the
Charter to attract more foreign capital, and that he is not
seeking political reforms like the extension of term limits.
</P>
<P>
The president said that there would be a ceremonial signing of
the covenant by himself, Senate President Blas Ople and House
Speaker Manuel Villar Jr. at "anytime within this week."
</P>
<P>
Ople, a member of the 1986 Constitutional Commission that
drafted the present constitution, said this covenant is meant to
convince the public that Estrada has no hidden political agenda in
proposing the Constitutional Corrections for Development (Concord)
process.
</P>
<P>
Ople said the tripartite covenant, which defines the scope of
the constitutional amendments, will have the force and effect of a
law.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Estrada also reiterated his appeal to some
lawmakers not to pursue their personal interests and concentrate
instead on coming up with concrete measures to improve the
people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
Political reforms, he added, can be taken up by the next
administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada started the Concord process by creating the Preparatory
Commission on Constitutional Reforms, which he tasked to study
proposed constitutional amendments and come up with its report by
the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign capital appears to be the only way of closing
the widening gap in investments that the government needs to
create jobs, improve the delivery of basic services and gear up
local industries for rapid globalization into the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
