<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Considers Readjusting Telecommunications Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 28 (Xinhua)-- China is planning to readjust
its telecommunications fees to conform with the international
price situation, said Wu Jichuan, minister of Information Industry
here today.
</P>
<P>
Wu told Xinhua that compared with nearby countries, China's
local telephone calls and mobile phone calls are less expensive,
but Internet service providers (ISP) and the cost of international
phone calls are both more expensive.
</P>
<P>
"The fees adjustment will bring down the income of the
telecommunications industry in the short period, but with the
increase of users, the sector stands to win in the long-term," he
said.
</P>
<P>
China lowered the its ISP charges and telephone installation
fees in March, resulting in an income decrease of 12.5 billion
yuan to the telecommunications industry, but the number of
Internet users and telephone users has increased significantly.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that China's information industry will
gradually focus on the development of micro-electronics, software,
information infrastructure construction, and market construction,
because at present China supplies itself with less than 20 percent
of its micro-electronics products.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese electronics industry ranks fifth in the world in
terms of production scale. In 1998, China produced 2.9 million
computers, 8.6 million mobile phones, and 36 million color TV sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNESCO to Build 400 Secondary Schools for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) will
build 400 secondary schools for Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This project is part of a cooperation agreement signed on
Monday by UNESCO's Deputy Director-General Colin Paul and Iraqi
Education Minister Fahd Salim Ash-Shakrah, said INA.
</P>
<P>
Paul said after the signing ceremony that UNESCO will also
supply books and equipment to Iraqi students.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO will write off some of Iraq's debts to provide
necessary funds for the project of building schools, said Paul.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq is one of the leading countries in education
before the U.N. sanctions were imposed on the country in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
However, "embargo has crippled all the chances to improve the
education system because of the U.N. Security Council's ban on the
imports of pencils, papers and other basic prerequisites for
education," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the U.N. sanctions will be lifted
soon, saying the embargo has caused grave impacts on education,
culture and science of the country.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ash-Shakrah said that cooperation with UNESCO
goes beyond the scope of building schools. "There are many other
projects in the field of culture and science," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO delegation led by Paul is paying a several-day
visit to Iraq to examine the effects of U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Sees Earth-Shaking Changes in Past Half Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Earth-shaking changes have
taken place in Sichuan Province, southwest China, in the past half
century, where 85 million residents now have access to a
sufficient food supply, the most prominent achievement for the
province since 1949, the year New China was founded.
</P>
<P>
So said Zhang Zhongwei, acting governor of the province, during
an interview.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province, known as "the Land of Abundance," had the
largest population, 110 million, of any provinces in the country,
until its city of Chongqing was promoted to Municipality status in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Grain output in Sichuan rose from 10 million tons in 1949 to
more than 36 million tons in 1998, with per capita grain
consumption exceeding 420 kg last year. Sichuan accounts for one-
third of the grain produced in ten provinces and cities in western
China, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The local GDP reached 358 billion yuan last year, indicating an
average annual growth rate of more than nine percent over the past
half century. Sichuan now contributes one-third of the GDP for all
of western China.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has transformed the famous water conservancy project at
Dujiangyan, which was built 2,200 years ago and turned the Chengdu
Plain into fertile land. The total irrigated area benefited from
the project has been expanded to 6.67 million hectares from the
former 180,000 hectares, creating one of the largest gravity-
irrigated areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
The province has also become the most important grain and non-
staple food producer in the country's western region, and now has
more than 1.21 million township enterprises, which contribute to
half of its total industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
The province has also made great headway in industry, science
and technology, transportation, and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Expressways there now extend for more than 400 km, with more
than 700 km now under construction. By the end of 1998, a total of
more than 80,000 km of highways had opened to traffic in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan also has become the country's largest base for
developing water energy, and its local "Silicon Valley" in
Mianyang has attracted worldwide attention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger Says China's Accession to WTO Achievable in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger said here today that he believes China's
accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO) is achievable this
year.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at a luncheon reception at the ongoing Fortune
Global Forum, Kissinger said that China's participation in the WTO
"should be in the interest of China, of the U.S. and of the world
community." He said the negotiations failed in April because of
domestic American politics, and that it cannot resume exactly at
that same point.
</P>
<P>
"But with the wisdom of both sides, ...I believe a solution
should be achievable within this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. diplomat, who was met by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin here on Monday, said that maintaining a cooperative
relationship between China and the U.S. will be in the interest of
both nations and indeed the entire world. Therefore the two
countries should resolve their disputes through diplomatic
channels on the basis of mutual understanding and accommodation.
</P>
<P>
The two have no conflict on principle issues, although they are
quite different in their ideology and culture, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot consider that we can have stability and progress in
Asia if China and the United States are in a cold war with each
other," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
China has experienced great changes over the past two decades,
and its opening to the outside over the past 10 years was much
greater than that of the previous 200 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the U.S. should continue its "one China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Every American president,...has agreed that Taiwan should be
part of China," he said. "Every single American president, of both
parties, including President Reagan, who explicitly stated, and
President Clinton repeated last year, that America affirms 'one
China,' and not 'two Chinas' or 'one China, one Taiwan.'"
</P>
</TEXT>
