<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches Urgent Meeting to Solve Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A tripartite meeting has been
launched to find way out of the current crisis forcing the
close-down of the 3.8- billion-U.S. dollar Nigeria Liquefied
Natural Gas Plant.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the government, the management of the Nigeria
Liquefied Natural Gas Ltd. and local traditional leaders opened in
Port Harcourt, capital of Nigeria's east Rivers State, Monday
after President Olusegun Obasanjo paid a one-day visit to Bonny
Island, Rivers State, where the plant is located.
</P>
<P>
Basically, Bonny indigenes want five managerial positions in
the gas plant, employment of 50 skilled hands, supply of
electricity and water and strict adherence to the mitigation
measures in the Environmental Impact Assessment report on the
project, according to sources at Monday's meeting in Port
Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door parley was convened to clear "the grey areas"
which Obasanjo did not address during his visit to the plant, the
Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the restive youths Sunday, the president
stressed that the face-off between the community and the companies
was hurting the country's foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for training program to engage the
indigenes, appealing, however, for time to attend to their
demands.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo also told the youths that the fulfilment of their
wishes depended on the restoration of peace in the area.
</P>
<P>
The president had admitted that failure to plan for the future
of the youth who worked at the construction site of the Nigeria
Liquefied Natural Gas, was responsible for the shut-down of the
multi-billion plant.
</P>
<P>
The huge plant in southeast Nigeria has been closed since last
Thursday, following the continued siege to the plant by local
protesters.
</P>
<P>
The project is Nigeria's largest joint venture jointly invested
by Nigeria's National Petroleum Corporation, Anglo-Dutch Shell,
Italian group Agip and France's Elf and other major western oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's new civilian government has put high hopes on the
multi- billion-dollar plant in a bid to diversify its too much
reliance on oil export and reduce gas flaring causing severe
environment pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
