<HEADLINE> HK Exports in August Rise by 4.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total exports
continued to pick up in August 1999 as shown by the external trade
figures released Tuesday by the Census and Statistics Department (
CSD).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's value of total exports comprising re-exports and
domestic exports in August this year increased by 4.4 percent over
a year earlier to 124.3 billion HK dollars (15.93 billion U.S.
dollars), obtaining a surplus for the first time since January
1998, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman said the further pick-up in
Hong Kong's total exports in August was mainly led by a strong
recovery in demand in East Asia and sustained robust demand in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Exports to China's mainland should have also arrested its
downward trend since April 1998, in line with a distinct rebound
in the mainland's exports lately, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
With the further improvement in exports alongside the still
modest absorption of imports, Hong Kong's visible trade account
attained a surplus in August 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
Within the total, the value of re-exports rose by 6.7 percent
while the domestic exports decreased by 9.5 percent in August over
a year earlier, according to the CSD figures.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's value of imports in August also increased by 1.7
percent over a year earlier to 121.9 billion HK dollars (15.62
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, for the first eight months of 1999 as a whole, the
value of total exports was lower by 4.4 percent over a year
earlier, according to the CSD figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
