<HEADLINE> Pak PM Vows to Restore Peace in Karachi at All Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif Tuesday said strikes and rallies will not be allowed
to disturb peace and economic activity in Karachi, the country's
biggest commercial city.
</P>
<P>
"The government has been successful in maintaining peace in the
city and people are now satisfied," he was quoted by the
Associated Press of Pakistan as telling reporters while on a tour
of the southern province of Sindh, where Karachi is located.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the "law breakers" will not realize the
gravity of the situation unless they go out and earn a living on
their own.
</P>
<P>
"They would not have given strike calls if they had been used
to earning bread at their own," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's remarks came at a time when his government
has been facing waves after waves of strikes and rallies in the
port city and the whole Sindh Province during the past two months.
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen opposition parties have formed a grand
opposition alliance and called for strikes and anti-government
rallies in a bid to oust Sharif from his post.
</P>
<P>
They accuse the Sharif government of corruption and failure in
bringing the economy back on track after the nuclear tests last
year.
</P>
<P>
Police have carried out frequent operations to arrest
opposition leaders and workers to forestall those anti-government
rallies and demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that in doing so his government's aim is to restore
the old glories of Karachi and maintain peace which is the
prerequisite for the revival of economic activity.
</P>
<P>
"Revival of economic activity will then open up more job
opportunities and weed out frustration from among the masses.
There are infinite advantages if peaceful conditions prevail," he
remarked.
</P>
<P>
He added that it is a matter of great concern that foreign
governments imposed travel embargoes due to the law and order
situation in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
"Actions of politicians are confined to newspapers only whereas
people want peace alone," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "People want peace, employment and
bread. They have no fourth desire."
</P>
<P>
However, Sharif admitted that it is not an easy task to bring
economic prosperity to a country which faces international
sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
