<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: For Golan Settlers, Israeli Withdrawal Is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIBBUTZ EN ZIWAN, Golan Heights, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Since
Shsehf Sror bought a supermarket and a cafeteria from the
collective farm Kibbutz on the Golan Heights six months ago, he
has been wondering how long he can keep them.
</P>
<P>
As Israel is warming up for resuming peace talks with Syria,
Sror said he would not be surprised if being told some day to
abandon the kibbutz. "If the government decides to give the Golan
back to Syria for peace, then we will have to leave," Sror said.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to give up the Golan if we want to avoid wars
with Syria," said Susan Korda, a cashier in the supermarket.
Korda, who came from Britain and settled down in Golan 12 years
ago, estimated that 90 percent of the 260 members in this kibbutz
share her view.
</P>
<P>
The future of the Golan Heights, a strategic plateau Israel
captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East War, has been the
focus of the on-and-off talks between the two sides since the
Madrid Mideast peace conference in 1991. The latest talks broke
down in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, who swept to power
in the elections in May, has pledged to revive the peace talks on
all tracks, which were largely frozen during the era of his
hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He has also set an ambitious target of reaching a
comprehensive peace with the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon next
year.
</P>
<P>
Syria has insisted that no peace can be achieved without a full
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan overlooking a large part of
Israel and Syria. The Mount Hermon at the northern tip is an ideal
base for intelligence gathering and early-warning stations.
</P>
<P>
Besides its strategic importance, the Golan is also famous for
its fertile land and rich water resources. It had been known as
Syria's "grain field" before the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
Today, the 32 Jewish settlements set up since the end of the
1967 war on the plateau, with a population of 17,000, are among
major suppliers of farm produce in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Kibbutz En Ziwan, which has 60 families, is situated merely
two or three kilometers away from the current Israeli-Syrian
border. Large stretches of apple orchards and vineyards surround
houses with courtyards and lawns.
</P>
<P>
In this otherwise idyllic farm, red-and-yellow warning signs
of land mines were erected in roadside fields. Within a stone's
throw is a base of U.N. disengagement forces and the "ghost
village" of Kuneitra, a deserted Syrian village.
</P>
<P>
Built immediately after the 1967 war, En Ziwan was destroyed by
Syrian shelling in the 1973 Yom Kippur War, during which Syria had
at one time regained most of the Heights. Photos hanging on the
wall of the cafeteria depicted a scene of what happened to the
Kibbutz - women and children were being evacuated by buses and
people were rushing to underground bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to see my kids going to war again," said Sror,
the father of three. "We fought with Egypt, we fought with Jordan,
now we are at peace with them. So what did we fight for? It's for
nothing."
</P>
<P>
Well established in the Heights, Sror is reluctant to leave. "I
really don not know what I'm going to do after leaving all these
behind," he said, "we all want peace, but the problem is how, how
much we should give back to Syria."
</P>
<P>
He said he would stay as long as possible though he understood
this was not very realistic.
</P>
<P>
Such conflicting mentality is quite popular throughout the
country. A survey on the future of Golan conducted early this year
showed that 73 percent of Israelis were willing to give back none
or only a small portion of the plateau, but 54 percent believed
that Israel would anyhow give the Golan to Syria within the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
In the May election, about 60 percent of the Golan settlers,
traditionally Labor supporters, voted for the dovish Barak.
However, hundreds of them signed a letter to Barak, declaring that
this huge support should not be interpreted as an endorsement for
a withdrawal from the Golan.
</P>
<P>
Only last week, Golan Regional Council Head Yehuda Wolman
announced that a new Israeli neighborhood of 52 homes would be
built in the region soon, a project approved by the Netanyahu
government,
</P>
<P>
Left-wing politicians criticized the house-building plan as
Israel and Syria are going to the negotiating table, saying it
would turn out to be a "waste of money."
</P>
<P>
Since Barak's election, a considerable number of messages of
peace have been exchanged between Israel and Syria through Jordan,
Europe and the U.S.. But the two sides are at loggerhead over how
the talks should be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Barak has claimed readiness to make "painful" territorial
concession on the Golan Heights, but has been vague on to what
extent.
</P>
<P>
As the Israeli-Palestinian talks back on track, the talks
between Israel and Syria have taken the central stage in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, both Israel and Syria have been
intensifying their diplomacy seeking international support on
their starting positions.
</P>
<P>
In various occasions recently, Barak has expressed belief that
the Israeli-Syrian talks can be revived in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We are talking about one year to reach peace agreement," Sror
said, "but we need two or three generations to build peace." The
trauma caused by decades of hostility between the two peoples need
time to heal, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
