<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Release Iraqi POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- An unspecific number of Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs) are to be released unilaterally by Iran on
Wednesday, it was announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier Mohammad Balar, the spokesman and head of the Public
Relations and Publicity Department of POWs Commissions, said that
the Iraqi POWs will be released on the occasion of 100th birth
anniversary of late Iranian spiritual leader Imam Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis will be released in the presence of a red cross
representative.
</P>
<P>
Balar said that 55,438 Iraqi POWs have been released by Iran so
far, including 6,078 unilaterally, while Iraq freed 39,417 Iranian
POWs since since 1981. There are still 2,806 Iranian POWs being
kept in Iraqi prisons, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors fought a eight-year bloody war from 1980 to
1988, in which some 1 million people from both sides were killed.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has become one of the major obstacles that
impeded improvement of relations between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
