<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safe Corridor to Open Two Days behind Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The southern safe corridor
linking the Gaza Strip and Tarkumia near the West Bank city of
Hebron will be inaugurated Sunday, two days behind schedule due to
the weekend holiday of Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli sources said the opening ceremony might
be preceded by the signing of a protocol on the operation of the
passage.
</P>
<P>
The corridor will be open to all Palestinians in Gaza and the
West Bank, seven days a week, from sunrise to sunset or 10 hours
at the least one day. However, it will be closed three days each
year on the occasion of certain feasts.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, any Palestinian who wants to pass the
corridor can apply to the Palestinian side for a "safe corridor
card." The card, valid between three months to one year, can be
easily renewed.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that the "safe corridor card" does not
mean a passport for the holders to enter any Israeli town.
</P>
<P>
For those Palestinians whom Israel guards against for security
reasons, special cards may be issued enabling them to use special
buses running between the West Bank and Gaza three times a week.
</P>
<P>
The opening of passage routes is part of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace agreement signed recently in Egyptian
Red Sea resort Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the northern safe corridor linking
Gaza and the West Bank town of Ramallah will open to traffic
several months after the operation of the southern corridor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
