<HEADLINE> Australian PM Backs Off From Howard Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard backed further off from the so-called Howard doctrine
Tuesday amid claims that it had pushed Australia's regional
relations to a new low.
</P>
<P>
Howard had already disputed a magazine article which said he
wanted Australia to be the U.S. deputy in Asia as the regional
policeman.
</P>
<P>
Howard told the ruling coalition's parliamentarians Tuesday
that he had not called his plan for Australia to play a greater
role in regional affairs "the Howard doctrine."
</P>
<P>
"The reference to a doctrine was made by others not by him," a
coalition spokesman said. 
</P>
