<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Demand Saudi Prior Notice on Execution of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Monday demanded that
Saudi Arabian government should give proper briefing before
execution of Nigerians according to  Arabic laws.
</P>
<P>
Conferring with the Saudi Arabian Ambassador to Nigeria Anwar
Abd-Rabbuh in Abuja, Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Minister of State,
Dubem Onyia, also sought for greater cooperation by Saudi
authorities with their Nigerian counterparts, in making
participation of the yearly pilgrimage Hajj less cumbersome for
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Tuesday quoted the
minister as saying: "when offences are committed, we will like
prior contact with our government before the full wrath of the
law is brought to bear on our nationals."
</P>
<P>
"We are going to re-organize the way Hajj operations have been
done in the past to make it easier for all parties," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with the Saudi envoy, who had insisted that those who
come to the country have to play according to the rules, Onyia
pointed out that Nigerian and Saudi officials needed to work more
closely with each other to eliminate present lapses.
</P>
<P>
Abd-Rabbuh had requested for the greater commitment of the
Nigerian government to curbing drug trafficking by pilgrims. He
assured that the kingdom would remain a good ally of Nigeria in
the new democratic dispensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Appeals for Debt Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Vice-President Atiku
Abubakar has appealed to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
the World Bank to help reduce or cancel the over 28-billion-U.S.
dollar debt owed by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an investors' forum in Washington, the U.S.,
Abubakar said that this would provide brighter chances for the
country to improve its economy, Nigeria's This Day newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president noted that his country's external debt
burden is too heavy to bear and could remain a deterrence to
growth and development if the creditors refuse to grant it debt
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria's external debt stock stood at 28.49
billion dollars in March this year compared to 28.77 billion
dollars by last December. The debt service ratio is about 40
percent in 1998 and the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar pointed out that principles and maturities in 1999
amounted to 3.15 billion dollars, out of which 1.68 billion
dollars were budgeted for.
</P>
<P>
This had left an unfunded balance of 1.47 billion dollars which
will be added to the arrears, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Nigeria is prepared to consider strategies for
reducing its debt burden on the basis of the Naples Terms which
can qualify the country for substantial Net Present Value debt
reduction, a six-year moratorium, and repayment over 23 years.
</P>
<P>
At the investors' forum, IMF Deputy Managing Director
Shigemitsu Sugisaki said that the IMF and Nigeria is scheduled to
have discussion in January next year with the Nigerian government
on the possibility for reducing its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Sugisaki said that by January 2000, Nigeria and IMF must have
concluded a standby arrangement which would set the stage for
negotiations on debt reduction with the international monetary
agencies.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the IMF and the World Bank would help Nigeria
in designing a comprehensive reform program which would include
the development and full liberalization of the nation's foreign
exchange system.
</P>
<P>
The IMF official noted that Nigerians had the capacity to turn
their economy around, adding that the abundant resources in the
west African country could not be developed due to frustrations
created by bureaucracy and government intervention and
manipulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
