<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Urges Inventors to Ensure Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo Monday urged indigenous scientific inventors to
inculcate the culture of standard engineering design and
practices into their operations, to ensure speedy technological
growth of the country.
</P>
<P>
Represented by Science and Technology Minister, Chief Ebitimi
Banigo, at the first National Conference on Engineering Design,
Abuja, Obasanjo said proper engineering design was an important
tool for national economic development, reported the Guardian, a
leading Nigerian newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bemoaning the people's attitude towards made-in-Nigeria
automotive parts, Obasanjo emphasized that the country could not
continue to live under the stigma of inferior quality for
products emanating from the nation' s small and medium scale
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The government, according to him, believed firmly that it was
only through strict adherence to design specifications in
manufacturing that made-in- Nigeria goods would appeal to the
people.
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, asked local engineers and investors to take up
the challenge of ensuring the country's rapid technological
advancement.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Science and Technology, Mrs. Pauline
Tallen, explained the objective of the conference which is to
include identifying and assessing the current level of
engineering design capability and practice in the country and to
prepare a blueprint for fostering engineering design as a tool
for national economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
