<HEADLINE> African Foundation Wins $1M Humanitarian Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The African Medical and
Research Foundation has won the one-million-U.S. dollar Conrad N.
Hilton Humanitarian Prize for its efforts to improve Africa's
health care, information from New York said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights (UNHCR)
and the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation jointly announced that the
world's largest humanitarian award honors the foundation's
tireless commitment to bring health care services to the most
remote areas of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The foundation, with 95 percent of its staff Africans, is
providing services that range from primary care to rehabilitative
surgery in nine east and southern African countries, and is
training and consulting in 12 additional African countries.
</P>
<P>
The organization was the first to provide reconstructive
surgical care in east Africa with its Flying Doctors service
launched 42 years ago by three surgeons.
</P>
<P>
John Batten, director general of the foundation, said that his
organization plans to use the one million dollars to strengthen
and expand its innovative HIV/AIDS and malaria prevention
programs, as well as increase its training programs that have
already prepared surgical specialists in 120 hospitals and trained
several thousand health workers, who have in turn trained tens of
thousands more at the village level.
</P>
<P>
The Conrad N. Hilton Humanitarian Prize which was established
in 1996 is presented annually to a charitable or non-governmental
organization that has made extraordinary contributions toward
alleviating human suffering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
