<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound, Dollar Rises in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded sharply
in Tokyo Tuesday, boosted by the U.S. dollar's rise against the
yen, with the key Nikkei index closing above 17,000 for the first
time in three trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange soared 504.64 points, or 3.00
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,325.70.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 39.91 points, or 2.79 percent, to 1,469.
29.
</P>
<P>
After opening at the day's low of 16,892.46, the Nikkei rose
steadily, helped by the dollar's strength and Monday's rise on
Wall Street, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors were net buyers, boosting market sentiment
after the Nikkei index had lost more than 1,100 points during the
previous three trading days, they said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section edged up to 350.46 million shares
from 346.76 million Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 843 to 335, with 149 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar rose above 106
yen level, buoyed by continued fears of possible joint action by
the Group of Seven (G-7) nations to rein in the appreciation of
the yen.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 106.50-53 yen, up from 106.
25-28 yen at 9 a.m., and from 105.75-85 yen in New York overnight.
The U.S. currency was traded at 104.12-15 yen in Tokyo late Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
