<HEADLINE> Japan Picks Foreign Investment Group as Possible LTCB Buyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Financial
Reconstruction Commission (FRC) said Tuesday it would open
priority negotiations with an investor group led by U.S.
investment house Ripplewood Holdings LLC on sale of the
nationalized Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB).
</P>
<P>
A deadline has been set for an agreement on the sale by the end
of November, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The investor group includes Deutsche Bank AG of Germany, ABN-
AMRO Bank of the Netherlands, and Mellon Bank, GE Capital Corp.
and PaineWebber Inc., it said.
</P>
<P>
If the sale of LTCB to the investor group is realized, LTCB
will become the first major Japanese commercial bank to come under
foreign ownership.
</P>
<P>
LTCB, one of Japan's three long-term credit banks, has been
under state control since last October following its failure under
huge losses stemming from bad loans.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
