<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Launch Global Movement for Active Aging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- More than two million people
of all ages will stage a "walkathon" worldwide on October 2 as the
World Health Organization (WHO) launches a global movement for
active aging.
</P>
<P>
The million-walk will be the biggest health promotion event in
history by and for older people in more than 1,500 cities in 86
countries, the United Nations health agency announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The walk, known as the Global Embrace, also celebrates the UN
1999 International Year of Older Persons.
</P>
<P>
Active aging is WHO's response to the rapidly growing number of
men and women over 60 in the world's population. There are now
about 590 million older people, according to WHO estimates. In
just 25 years, that number will double to 1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
By active aging, WHO refers to the process of seizing and
optimizing opportunities for physical, social and mental well-
being throughout the entire life in order to extend life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
The global walk will follow the rising sun from Fiji, New
Zealand and New Caledonia, and continue non-stop through more than
1,500 large cities and small towns in Australia, Japan, China, the
Philippines, India, the Middle East, Europe and the Americas, and
end once again in the Pacific, according to the WHO schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0177 </DOCNO>
