<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Urges Africa to eradicate Cattle Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Africa must eradicate cattle
contagious bovine pleuropneumonia and east coast fever (corridor
disease) so as to ensure livestock growth and sustainable
development, Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) said.
</P>
<P>
Opening an international workshop in Lusaka on monitoring the
corridor disease in Africa on Monday, FAO country representative
Gana Diagne said cattle diseases in the region have had a negative
impact on the development of the agricultural sector as cattle was
the major source of animal draught power.
</P>
<P>
Zambian newspaper, the post, Tuesday quoted Diagne as saying
there was urgent need for researchers and scientists to find
methods of combating the diseases if agriculture was to improve.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which has drawn researchers and scientists from
east and central Africa, southern Africa, America, Austria and
Sweden, is aimed at sensitizing researchers to use serological
tests.
</P>
<P>
Diagne said monitoring of the disease using enzyme immunoassays
was being promoted by FAO.
</P>
<P>
He said the international Atomic Energy Agency was capable of
detecting clinically infected animals and is currently being used
in some parts of Africa, Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
