<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Prices Force Tobacco Sales Closed in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- All the three tobacco auction
floors in Malawi have been closed with growers grumbling about the
decline in prices, Zambian newspaper, The Post, reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Prices are going down at a time when the cost of production is
rising," Malawian Agriculture Minister Aleke Banda was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed this mainly to lack of buyer
competition at the close of the selling season on September 10
when burley fetched as low as 0.5 U.S. dollars per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Sales opened in April with prices averaging over 15 percent
higher than last year's. The highest price was pegged at almost
2.25 U.S. dollars per kilogram, while the lowest was at slightly
over one dollar per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, commercial banks are reluctant also to provide input
loans. For the past three years, farmers have failed to produce
enough and meet the buyers' demands due to increases in the price
of agricultural inputs.
</P>
<P>
In all, a total of 125 million kilograms of tobacco worth about
200 million dollars have been sold at the three floors, far below
the buyers total requirement of 180 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The fact that tobacco prices are getting increasingly lower is
not exactly accidental, the Zambian newspaper noted. There are
world-wide forces against tobacco's prosperity, and the tobacco
market is projected to keep shrinking.
</P>
<P>
Malawi is one of the world's biggest exporters of burley
tobacco. It also produces five other types of tobacco including
flue cured and dark fire cured, which are sold to more than 70
countries.
</P>
<P>
Malawi has started its own drive to reduce over-dependence on
tobacco. The crop accounts for 70 percent of the country's
foreign earnings, and about 1.5 million Malawians eke their
livelihoods from the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
