<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Indignant at Anti-China U.S. Defense Act: FM Spokeswoman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua)-- China is intensely indignant
at and strongly opposes the anti-China U.S. Defense Authorization
Act, said Foreign Ministry Spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Fiscal Year Defense Authorization Act, which was
passed recently by the U.S. Congress, contains many anti-China
clauses proposed by a small number of congressmen, the spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's routine press conference, Zhang described
the act as attempting to interfere in China's internal affairs and
impair Sino-U.S. relationship by making use of such issues as
Taiwan, China's construction for national defense, Sino-U.S.
scientific exchange, the alleged China "espionage case" and non-
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
It needs to be pointed out, said Zhang, that once the clauses
become law, they will severely harm the exchange and cooperation
between the two countries in many fields, and poison bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side demands that the U.S. administration fully
realize the disastrous and damaging nature and bad impact of the
act, and from the overall interest of the Sino-U.S. relations,
take immediate and effective measures to prevent it from becoming
law, in order not to set any new obstacles for the improvement and
development of Sino-U.S. ties, Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
