<HEADLINE> Thai PM to Discuss E. Timor Issue With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen will visit Thailand this week to discuss the
peacekeeping process in East Timor with Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A senior Foreign Ministry official was quoted as saying on
Tuesday that Cohen would arrive here on Friday and would then meet
Chuan in his capacity as the Thai defense minister and Armed
Forces Chief Gen. Mongkol Amportpisit, to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
The trip is part of Cohen's eight-day visit to Australia and
countries in Southeast Asia, including Thailand, Indonesia,
Singapore and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chuan told TNA that the government had decided to
send 1,500 Thai troops to take part in the international
peacekeeping force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 33 Thai soldiers left for Darwin of
Australia to join an advance multinational peacekeeping force in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The second batch of 300 Thai combat soldiers are to leave
Bangkok on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
