<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hopes for Stability in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- China today expressed the
hope that the stability in East Timor will be restored according
to relevant United Nations resolution, and it will make a
contribution to maintaining peace and stability there within the U.
N. framework.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue made the remarks at a
press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Chinese government has been concerned about
the situation in East Timor, adding that the United Nations
Security Council passed a resolution on September 15 which
authorizes a multi-national peace-keeping troop to enter East
Timor based on humanitarian consideration.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that China believes that it is not
appropriate for the human rights commission to convene a special
meeting on East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Further more, it will not help settle the issue if a human
rights resolution on East Timor is passed through consultations by
different countries concerned, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
She said that China, together with other Asian countries, voted
against a motion that the U.N. would establish an international
investigation into human rights violations in East Timor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
