<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Follows Killing of Shiite Leader in Pak City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Violence broke out in the
Pakistani city of Dera Ismail Khan, some 300 kilometers south of
Islamabad, after the killing of a senior leader of a Shiite group
in a terrorist attack on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified gunmen shot dead Secretary General of Shiite
Tehreek-e-Jafria Pakistan (TJP) Khurshid Anwar, whose daughter and
bodyguard in the same car were also killed. Anwar's wife was
injured in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Tension gripped the town and angry TJP activists took to the
streets and burned six shops of the rival Sunni Sipah-e-Sahaba.
They set tires on fire and blocked roads, according to sources
from the town.
</P>
<P>
The local civil administration called out paramilitary troops
in a bid to control the situation, sealing off the city and
putting the neighboring districts on alert. Many people closed
their shops after receiving the news of the killing.
</P>
<P>
The divisional president of TJP, Ghulam Abbas, has accused
three Sipah-e-Sahaba leaders of involvement in the case.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate response from Sipah-e-Sahaba. The two
groups usually accuse each other of killings their respective
activists.
</P>
<P>
The city of Dera Ismail Khan has been in tension after the
local administration banned the entry of Sipah-e-Sahaba leader
Maulana Azam Tariq, who was scheduled to address an Islamic
conference last month. A worker of the group was killed when
unknown persons opened fire on the group's procession against the
ban on the entry of Tariq in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
