<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Still Occupies Egyptian Land: Egyptian Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is preparing for a fresh
diplomatic battle with Israel to "restore the last bit of land the
Jewish state has continued to occupy since 1949," the Egyptian
Gazette newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the prevalent conclusion, Taba, a town close to the
border with Israel, "was not the last piece of land" Egypt has
recovered from Israel, "as Israel is still occupying Om i-Rashrash
area west of (Israel's) Eilat Port," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Israel handed over Taba to Egypt in 1988 after the countries
solved their disputes through international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has formed a special negotiation team to pursue the
uphill task of claiming this piece of land after a special expert
committee had found historical evidences supporting Egypt's right
to the claim, the English-language paper added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel has assigned an American team to look into
the issue, a move which the newspaper said clearly indicated
Israel's desire to get Washington involved.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government paper accused Israel of trying to package
Egypt's claim as casus belli after the Jewish state failed to
respond to the historical evidences which the paper said affirm
beyond doubt that Om i-Rashrash belongs to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Salah Selim, a strategic studies professor at
Nasser Military Academy, as saying that the triangle of Om
i-Rashrash was under Egyptian sovereignty according to
Egyptian-Palestinian border arrangements before the British
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied this piece of land in the 1948 Arab-Israeli
war, the paper said without specifying its area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
