<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Praises Australian Economic Strength: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan had singled out Australia for praise over
the way it weathered the Asian economic downturn, Australian Prime
Minister John Howard said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan made the comments during a speech to the World
Bank/International Monetary Fund meetings this week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I had a look at Dr. Greenspan's remarks," Howard told the
parliament. "They are always worth reading."
</P>
<P>
"Despite its close trade and financial ties to Asia, the
Australian economy exhibited few signs of the contagion from
contiguous economies arguably because Australia already had well
developed capital markets as well as a sturdy banking system,"
Howard quoted Greenspan as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Greenspan's comments should be highly regarded.
</P>
<P>
"It has now been recognized at the highest economic level in
the world what a strong, robust, well-run, well-regulated economy
is Australia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard also mentioned the former Labor government of Bob Hawke
as contributing to that strength.
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared on this occasion ... to give the Hawke
government in particular credit for some of the steps that it
took in relation to the Australian financial system," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But since we came to office ... the government has taken a
large number of steps to further strengthen the Australian banking
and financial system," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
