<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Wins World No Tobacco Day 1999 Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Ministry of
Environment has won the World Health Organization's World No
Tobacco Day 1999 Medal for its contribution to smoking control in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the International Consultation on
Tobacco and Youth held here Tuesday, WHO presented this year's
World No Tobacco Day Medal to the ministry that has progressively
made more public places smoke-free over the past 30 years through
the Smoking (Prohibition in Certain Places) Act.
</P>
<P>
A citation says the ministry is honored with this medal
"because of the strong support for three decades from the Ministry
of the Environment in Singapore for well-enforced legislative
measures enabling smoke-free environments and the protection of
the health of non-smokers."
</P>
<P>
Singapore introduced the Smoking (Prohibition in Certain
Places) Act in 1970 to encourage smokers to kick the deadly habit
and protect non-smokers from the hazardous cigarette smoke and the
government has continued to publicize the need for tobacco control
over the years.
</P>
<P>
The International consultation on Tobacco and Youth, the first-
ever convened, is jointly held by the Singapore Cancer Society,
the Singapore Ministry of Health and WHO to highlight the
effective approaches and interventions for prevention and
reduction of tobacco use among children and adolescents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Philippine Telephone Firms Agree to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Long Distance
Telephone corporation (PLDT), the country's leading fixed-line
telephone company, signed Tuesday a formal agreement to acquire
Smart Communications, the country's leading cellular phone
company.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Pangilinan, PLDT's president and CEO, said in a
statement that the PLDT will acquire Smart by issuing 35.1 million
new common shares to Smart's shareholders at a value of 37.9
billion pesos (947.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The enlarged PLDT -- combining its own activities with those of
the Pilipino Telephone Corporation subsidiary and Smart -- will
initially have more than 1.85 million fixed-line customers and
approximately 1.34 million cellular phone customers.
</P>
<P>
Pangilinan said, "These transactions reflect the consolidation
in the worldwide telecommunications industry and will create a
stronger, more efficient PLDT."
</P>
<P>
The transactions will enable the PLDT to offer
fully-integrated, high-quality telecommunications services,
ranging from traditional fixed line and cellular phone networks to
high-technology Internet access, Pangilinan said.
</P>
<P>
He said they will also lead to significant cost savings by
combining overlapping operations in such areas as marketing,
information technology and customer service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
