<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA -- A senior Chinese official has urged the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to continue with its efforts to make
certain countries sign international treaties on nuclear
proliferation prevention.
</P>
<P>
At the opening here Monday of the 43rd annual conference of the
United Nations nuclear watchdog agency, Zhang Huazhu, chairman of
the China Atomic Energy Authority, said that it goes against the
trend of peace and development for some countries to continue
developing nuclear weapons and refuse joining the Comprehensive
Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and the Treaty on the Non-proliferation of
Nuclear Weapons. (IAEA-Proliferation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Executive directors of the World Bank on Monday
unanimously endorsed a proposal for the reappointment of James D.
Wolfensohn, 65, as President of the World Bank for a further term
of five years beginning June 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the World Bank said executive directors, noting
the significant achievements of Mr. Wolfensohn's first four years
in office, paid tribute to his leadership, vision and
contributions to the cause of poverty reduction. (World Bank-
Chief-Reappointment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- The average price of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Country's basket of seven crudes remained at a high of
22.3 U.S. dollars per barrel last week, the Vienna-based OPEC
Secretariat announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The oil Cartel's average oil price over the week was basically
on a par with the previous week's average of 22.31 U.S. dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Since OPEC oil ministers reached an agreement to cut production
to shore up prices in March, the organization's average oil price
has more than doubled, exceeding its benchmark price of 21 U.S.
dollars per barrel. (OPEC-Oil Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand has finally agreed to send 1,500 troops to
East Timor, Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The final decision came after a meeting, on Monday, between
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, also defense minister, and the
military top brass led by gen. Mongkol Ampornpisit, supreme
commander of the Thai armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a slight drop from 1,778 troops
originally planned. It was reported that Chuan wanted to send only
as many as necessary to join the international peacekeeping force
in East Timor. (Thailand-East Timor-Peacekeeping Force)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chinese Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng urged
here Monday multilateral development institutions to shift their
focus and improve the overall world economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Their focus should be shifted from emergency assistance to
lessons-learning, consolidation of world economy and making a long-
term development agenda, Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 60th meeting of the Development Committee of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Xiang
said that social policy, governance and institutional building are
undoubtedly essential to development and crisis prevention, but
the depth and breadth of these themes extend far beyond economic
development and crisis control. (IMF-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Former U.S. Vice-President Dan Quayle announced
Monday that he has decided to quit the presidential campaign
because of a lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
"Today I am announcing that I will no longer be a candidate for
president of the United States," Quayle said at a press conference
in Phoenix, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
He said that he never envisioned his Republican presidential
campaign ending this way, short on cash and before the first vote
was cast. (US-Election Campaign)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund and its members
Monday reached an agreement on financing the Initiatives of the
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) and Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF), the IMF told a news conference here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the main elements of the financing package
will enable the IMF to make its contribution to the HIPC
Initiative and to continue concessional lending for sustainable
growth and poverty reduction in its low-income member countries,
according to IMF. (IMF-HIPC-Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- The East Timor crisis would cost Australia at least
500 million Australian dollars (330 million U.S. dollars) by next
July and the final cost is unknown, Defense Minister John Moore
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moore told a defense conference at the Parliament House that no
effort has been spared to give Australian troops all they need to
restore security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"The final cost of the commitment cannot be known," Moore said.
(Australia-E. Timor-Cost)
</P>
