<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Launches Its First Hong Kong Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 28 (Xinhua) - Internet provider America
Online, Inc. (AOL) announced Tuesday that it had joined with China.
com Corporation, and its affiliate China Internet Corporation (CIC)
to launch AOL Hong Kong, the newest member of the AOL global
community.
</P>
<P>
The AOL Hong Kong service, the first Chinese language AOL
service, connects Hong Kong consumers to AOL's global community of
more than 18 million members for the first time, said Judy Lau,
managing director of the AOL Hong Kong service.
</P>
<P>
As Hong Kong's only full-service online provider, AOL Hong Kong
will offer the easiest, most convenient and enjoyable online
experience available with unique local content, features and
services and state-of-the-art communications tools in addition to
simplified access to the Internet, AOL said in a statement
announcing the launch of the service.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal in Hong Kong -- as around the world -- is to help
make the interactive medium a central and valuable part of people'
s lives," said Steve Case, AOL chairman.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, AOL is delighted to join with our partners,
China Internet Corp. and China.com Corp., in helping fuel Hong
Kong's development as a key Internet hub in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jackie Davies, president of AOL International, said that Hong
Kong, with its combination of high penetration of home computers,
rapid growth in Internet usage and tradition of quickly adopting
new technology, is a very attractive market for AOL.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to helping advance the interactive medium
here and across the Asia-Pacific region," Davies added.
</P>
<P>
The number of Internet users in Hong Kong, with a total
population of 6.8 million, has surpassed the one million mark, and
is continuing to grow, according to government officials.
</P>
<P>
Peter Yip, chief executive officer of China.com Corporation,
the leading pan-Asia integrated Internet service company, said: "
We are particularly pleased to be partnering with AOL since we
both strive to embrace local culture, language and interest in the
content and services that we provide."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has always been about an unparalleled blend of "
global" and "local" -- it is one of the world's most cosmopolitan
cities, Yip said.
</P>
<P>
"Our partnership will be instrumental in furthering Hong Kong's
competitiveness as we move into a rapidly maturing Internet and e-
commerce-based society," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
