<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Yangtze River Bridge Open To Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A new highway bridge across
the Yangtze River opened to traffic today in the city of Jiangyin
in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The bridge has a main span of 1,385 meters, the longest in
China and fourth in the world. The three bridges with longer spans
are in Japan, Denmark, and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The 3,071-meter bridge is in Jiangyin's suburbs on the lower
reaches of Yangtze. It is 196 meters high, or about the height of
a 70-story building.
</P>
<P>
It is the 15th bridge on the Yangtze, all of which were built
after the founding of the New China. Another 9 bridges are planned
for the next few years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Rules out Amending Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 28 (Xinhua) -- President Hosni Mubarak has
ruled out any imminent amendments of the constitution as called
for by the opposition, the Al Gomhuria newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think of any change in the constitution because I am
keen on the stability of the country," Mubarak said in an
exclusive interview on Monday with Al Gomhuria Chief Editor Samir
Ragab.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that he "will never allow" national stability to
"be shaken."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's words came one day after a national referendum
confirmed his fourth, six-year term in office. Some 80 percent of
Egypt's 24 million eligible voters went to the polls on Sunday and
gave the 71-year-old incumbent president 94 percent "Yes" vote.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to be sworn in on October 5 when the
parliament, the People's Assembly, convenes an extraordinary
session.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was the only candidate in the yes-or-no vote. Many
opposition parties called for a boycott, charging that the
referendum for the president is a sham. They asked Mubarak to
change the constitution to allow direct, multi-candidate
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Egyptian president reiterated that one of his
main occupations is to exert efforts to improve the living
standards of the limited-income classes.
</P>
<P>
"It is a tough responsibility. But I have pledged not to give
up my duty," Mubarak told Al Gomhuria, one of Egypt's major
pro-government newspapers.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to create more jobs for the country's young
people during his new term. "Youth will be at the center during
the next stage because they are the nation's mainstay in the 21st
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's unemployment rate is officially put at around 10
percent. More than 500,000 youngsters are estimated to enter the
labor market each year for the next 10-15 years.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak became president in 1981 after the assassination of the
former president, Anwar Sadat, by Islamic radicals. He was
re-elected in 1987 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
He has been highly respected internationally due to his efforts
to push forward the peace process with Israel. He has carried out
a privatization program, which has helped Egypt maintain one of
the best economic performances in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
