<HEADLINE> Xiaolangdi Yellow River Project to Start Storing Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The largest dam on the
Yellow River, China's second longest, has received state approval
and will start storing water early next month, according to
project sources.
</P>
<P>
If there is amply water supply in the upper reaches of the
river, the first power-generating unit at the dam will begin
generating power by the end of this year, according to Xiaolangdi
Administration officials.
</P>
<P>
A team of experts from the Ministry of Water Resources,
together with officials from Henan and Shanxi provinces inspected
the dam, facilities, and dredging in the dam area, September 24-26,
as entrusted by the State Planning Commission, and decided that
the dam is ready.
</P>
<P>
The project has used a billion U.S. dollars worth of World Bank
loans. It is a multi-purpose project in Henan Province for flood
control, ice control, dredging, water supply, and hydro-electric
power. It is expected to be completed by the year 2001 at a total
cost of 34.75 billion yuan (4.19 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project used 20.648 billion yuan (2.5 billion US dollars)
to complete construction of the main flood-control facilities and
relocate nearly 40,000 people living in the vicinity of the dam.
</P>
</TEXT>
