<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Disgraced figure skater
Tonya Harding, who is serving a life-time ban from the Olympics
following an attack incident on her American compatriot Nancy
Kerrigan, will re-start her career in professional competition
next month.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old will compete in ESPN's Professional Skating
Championships on October 18, her first event since her ban after
the attack on her rival before the 1994 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The ESPN event in Huntington, West Virginia, is exclusively for
professional skaters who are ineligible for Olympic competition.
</P>
<P>
Harding, who coaches about 15 young skaters at a Portland,
Oregon, skating club, has been training daily on her own for
several months.
</P>
<P>
The attack on Kerrigan came before the U.S. National
championships that were to decide the 1994 U.S. Olympic team.
Kerrigan was attacked by Harding's then husband and an associate
of his.
</P>
<P>
Harding went on to win the nationals but eventually was
stripped of her title and subsequently banned for life on charges
of hindering investigation. 
