<HEADLINE> E. Timor to Cost Australia 500 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The East Timor crisis would
cost Australia at least 500 million Australian dollars (330
million U.S. dollars) by next July and the final cost is unknown,
Defense Minister John Moore said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moore told a defense conference at the Parliament House that no
effort has been spared to give Australian troops all they need to
restore security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"The final cost of the commitment cannot be known," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
"But we estimate that between now and the end of this financial
year it will be at least 500 million Australian dollars, with more
needed to sustain and to reconstitute our ground forces," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Australian troops are leading a multinational force to restore
order in the territory following last month's vote for
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Moore said the multinational force would be followed by another
U.N. peacekeeping operation, hopefully within a year, to see East
Timor through to full independence.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard later told the parliament
the 500 million Australian dollars would cover 2,000 Australian
troops in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"I should point out that the 500 million Australian dollars was
based on a deployment of 2,000 for a period of six months or so,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"If it turns out to be more than that, the figure could be
significantly higher," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
