<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Cabinet to Say No to Honor Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Human rights and pressure
groups in Jordan are making progress in their campaign against
honor killings as the Cabinet has agreed to cancel penal code
clauses that pardons or reduces the penalties against the crime in
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet headed by Prime Minister Abdel Raouf al-Rawabdeh,
during a closed-door meeting last weekend, approved a
recommendation by the Justice Ministry to abolish Article 340 in
the Penal Code, the semiofficial Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The article included two clauses that either pardons or hands
down minor prison terms for men who kills their wives or female
relatives for actual or suspected illicit relationship with man
out of the wedlock.
</P>
<P>
The government said the decision to amend the penal code will
be presented to the parliament for approval during its next
ordinary session in November.
</P>
<P>
Campaigns to remove article 340 were getting more public
attention in the kingdom where dozens of young women were killed
by their husbands, brothers or fathers in the name of honor. At
least 14 Jordanian women died in honor killings this year.
</P>
<P>
Human rights activists have garnered at least 8,000 signatures
during the first months of a national campaign to abolish Article
340, which they said seriously discriminated against the rights of
women.
</P>
<P>
If Article 340 is finally eliminated, alleged honor killers
might face death sentences. Currently they are either pardoned or
received lenient sentences ranging from three months to two years
in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
