<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Shipper to Compensate for Pollution Off California Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Greek operator of a
Liberian-flagged tanker, which left a large oil spill off
California coast last year, has agreed to pay 9.4 million U.S.
dollars to settle criminal charges, according to reports from San
Francisco Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ship's captain, Dimitrios Georgantas, also accepted a three-
year probation during which he will be barred from any ship
calling at any U.S. port, U.S. officials announced.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney Robert Mueller said Georgantas disobeyed U.S.
Coast Guard orders and directed his crew to transfer oil into a
faulty tank -- a process which resulted in an estimated 3,000
gallons of oil spilling into the Pacific Ocean on Sept. 26, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Instead of informing the Coast Guard, as required by U.S. law,
Georgantas told his crew to keep quiet about the spill and
continued his tour toward South America, leaving behind a 24 km
long oil slick that fouled beaches south of San Francisco with
dead birds.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Coast Guard teams tracked the spill and eventually boarded
the tanker about 320 km west of Guatemala, finding a ruptured fuel
tank that they determined to be the spill's source.
</P>
<P>
"The coasts of California are a precious resource. Those who
criminally pollute that resource will be prosecuted criminally,"
Mueller said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Georgantas issued a statement of apology through his lawyer.
Under the plea agreement, which must still be approved by a judge,
charges against the ship's owner, Pearl Shipping Corp. of Liberia,
were dropped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
