<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Finance Initiatives for Helping Indebted Poor Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund and its members Monday reached an agreement on financing the
Initiatives of the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) and
Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF), the IMF told a
news conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the main elements of the financing package
will enable the IMF to make its contribution to the HIPC
Initiative and to continue concessional lending for sustainable
growth and poverty reduction in its low-income member countries,
according to IMF.
</P>
<P>
The main elements of the financing package, amounting to 3.9
billion Special Drawing Rights (SDRs) on an "as needed" basis (3.5
billion dollars in end-1998 net present value terms), comprise
contributions by member countries and by the IMF itself, said the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
The financing of the cost of the HIPC Initiative to the IMF is
projected to account for about two thirds of the IMF's total
financing requirement.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral pledges amount to about 1.5 billion SDRs "as needed"
and come from a wide cross-section of the IMF's membership,
demonstrating the broad support for the HIPC and ESAF initiatives,
the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Industrial countries as well as a large number of developing
countries, including some low-income countries that have had ESAF-
supported programs in the past, have also made pledges to the ESAF-
HIPC Trust.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's own contributions will amount to about 2.4 billion
SDRs "as needed."
</P>
<P>
The bulk of this will come from the investment income on the
profits from off-market transactions in gold of up to 14 million
ounces, estimated to provide about 1.8 billion SDRs "as needed."
</P>
<P>
The IMF will also contribute about 0.6 billion SDRs "as needed"
by foregoing compensation for the cost of administrative expenses
related to ESAF operations through 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia: Developing Countries' Interests Need to Be Protected at WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Tuesday it
wants to see the interests of developing countries protected
during negotiations in areas such as services at the World Trade
Organization (WTO) ministerial meeting in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
"We will ensure that the General Agreement on Trade in Services
(GATS) pays due consideration to the developing countries,"
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said when
officiating at an international workshop on "WTO and
Liberalization of World Trade in Services" here.
</P>
<P>
He said development of new disciplines on emergency safeguards
was crucial whereby liberalization in the WTO takes into account
national policy objectives and the level of development of
individual members, and that this would be of utmost priority to
developing countries in the light of the trend towards increasing
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which has often taken the lead in trying to prevent
the WTO from becoming a tool to prise open markets of developing
countries, will at Seattle like to see the development of these
new disciplines on emergency safeguards, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regretting that within the GATS negotiations and the WTO in
general, the voice of the developing countries is either seldom
heard or never in unison, Abdullah said Malaysia would at the
meeting also call for the development of sectoral guidelines on
domestic regulations relating to qualifications and procedures,
technical standards and licensing requirements for professional
services.
</P>
<P>
When it comes to recognizing educational qualifications, for
example, developing countries are once again at a disadvantage, he
said, adding the limited recognition accorded to qualifications
and experience gained in developing countries have hindered the
progress of these countries' service providers ability to gain
market access abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said that an economy might not be able to handle a sudden
influx of foreign service providers and that such a saturation
might adversely affect a country's economic policy objectives. "In
such an instance, developing countries must be allowed to protect
its economic interests," he added.
</P>
<P>
There is an inherent desire on the part of developing countries
to stay out of the process of liberalization to strengthen their
economic sectors so that they could play an equitable part in
world trade and so that globalization would have a more tangible
effect on the developing world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia sees no reason to hold back on the liberalization of
certain sectors as it is now calling for better market access in
various service sectors including professional services,
education, consultancy, health services, construction and tourism,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the developed countries will place as much
stress on these sectors as we have on financial services and
telecommunications. For instance, even in these areas where the
developing countries currently have a competitive advantage,
Malaysia is preparing for liberalization," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing consolidation of the Malaysian financial sector and
the continued development of its telecommunication firms indicate
that Malaysia is strengthening its domestic capacity in line with
eventual liberalization, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia does not favor rushing into a new round of
multilateral trade discussions at the WTO as it might lead to
agreements concerning three issues which are of great concern to
Malaysia and the developing nations, namely, investment,
competition policies and government procurement.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia made its position clear that it favors transparency
but not market access, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biman Carries 40 Pct Int'l Traffic to, From Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's national airline,
the Biman, is now carrying only about 40 percent of the total
international traffic (about 2 million passengers) to and from
Bangladesh, The Daily Star newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The scenario was the other way round eight years ago and the
declining market share of the Biman is taxing the nation's foreign
currency basket quite shockingly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Roughly 900 million U.S. dollars worth of business - both
passengers and cargo - goes to foreign carriers, and the amount
almost equals the net retention of the country's biggest export
earner, the garment industry.
</P>
<P>
Aviation sources were quoted as saying that half of the money
could be saved if the Biman or other Bangladeshi airlines (the
latter were not allowed to operate internationally) could make use
of the captive market.
</P>
<P>
But private airlines were not allowed to operate international
flights "to protect the national carrier," according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral air services agreement with foreign countries have,
in more case than not, failed to protect national interests in
granting traffic rights to foreign carriers, as the Biman has
failed to make use of its rightful share, the report said.
</P>
<P>
If the Biman could retain even 50 percent of the market share,
the country could be retaining at least 300 million dollars every
year in passenger and cargo revenue, more than five times the
entire tea exports (around 58 million dollars) of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The business is there, but we are not allowed to entry," a
local entrepreneur said.
</P>
<P>
"If foreign carriers are allowed to carry more passengers than
the Biman itself, then why should not the Biman and other domestic
carriers be part of the same team for Bangladesh and equalize the
score," he asked.
</P>
<P>
The Biman, as the designated airline of Bangladesh, has had a
much greater share granted by the bilateral air services
agreement, but inefficiency, corruption and lack of resources may
have handicapped the national airline, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Biman simply cannot operate 30 flights a week
granted by the air services agreement with India on two routes
because of lacking enough aircraft to make so many flights, the
report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
