<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes News Measures to Reform State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
decided to allow about 30 percent of the state-owned enterprises
of the country to sell, lease, transfer or entrust their
businesses in an effort to speed up their shift to profitability,
Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to make such enterprises more attractive
to potential investors by clarifying their legal status, according
to a Vietnamese government's decree that went into effect last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
It applies to the following state-run businesses: financially
independent enterprises, member enterprises of corporations with
total capital of less than 1 billion Vietnamese dong (VND) (about
72,000 U.S. dollars), and enterprises with state-allotted capital
of from 1 billion VND to 5 billion VND (360,000 U.S. dollars) that
have been unprofitable for a long time but have not yet gone
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations could apply to as many as 900 of Vietnam's
3,000 state-owned enterprises and up to 35 percent of such
businesses in Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
The decree of the Vietnamese government also stipulates that
those who have the right to buy a state-owned enterprise include
individual or worker collectives and businesses of any economic
sector excluding foreign-invested ones.
</P>
<P>
It also applies to Vietnamese citizens who are able by law to
set up or manage a business.
</P>
<P>
As for leasing, the decree states that the leaseholder can
either lease the whole state-owned business or only its property.
</P>
<P>
All measures are designed to ensure that the new business is
financially "healthy", Vietnam News quoted the local newspaper
Nguoi Lao Dong (Laborer) as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
