<HEADLINE> Dhaka Has Two Million Slum People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- As the slum people in the
capital of Bangladesh has now moved up to 2 million, experts here
stress the need for taking some effective measures to maintain the
healthy environment of the city.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by eminent urban expert Dr. Nazrul Islam and
sponsored by the government and the Asian Development Bank
detected three thousand and seven slums in the city area and found
fifty percent of those slums on private lands and under private
ownership.
</P>
<P>
According to a report published on Tuesday by The New Nation,
the study was initiated in 1996 and in the meantime the number of
slums have increased. The city population was enumerated at 6
million at that time and the study earmarked 1.5 million people as
slum dwellers.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Dr. Nazrul Islam indicated that the slum population
has now moved up to 2 million and the number of slums have also
increased.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the land tenancy policy in the country
upholds and ensures private ownership in land and as such,
evicting slum dwellers from the lands under private ownership will
be difficult. Besides, the development of the city as well as the
maintenance of its healthy environment will require some effective
measures to either evict and rehabilitate slum dwellers in order
to recover government and semi-government land or search for
alternative lands to facilitate development works.
</P>
<P>
Planned development of the city will also need some policy that
will help smooth supply of labor for development works and
productive activities within the city and reasonable dwelling
places for the working people, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
