<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Financial Agencies Urged to Shift Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Finance Minister
Xiang Huaicheng urged here Monday multilateral development
institutions to shift their focus and improve the overall world
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Their focus should be shifted from emergency assistance to
lessons-learning, consolidation of world economy and making a long-
term development agenda, Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 60th meeting of the Development Committee of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Xiang
said that social policy, governance and institutional building are
undoubtedly essential to development and crisis prevention, but
the depth and breadth of these themes extend far beyond economic
development and crisis control.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the multilateral development institutions in
these fields, Xiang said they are encouraged to put more emphasis
on experience dissemination without imposing a straight-jacket of
any kind on its support for institutional building in developing
countries based on their own specific situations.
</P>
<P>
"The social and institutional development in each county is
subject to the particular stage of its economic development, as
well as values, culture and tradition," he said, "Therefore, no
standardized social and structural model will work."
</P>
<P>
The experience of developed countries in terms of social and
institutional evolution can be of important relevance to
developing countries, but they should not be regarded as an
international standard that can be universally applied to all
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister urged multilateral agencies to put more
emphasis on exploring appropriate processes, rather than on
expediency.
</P>
<P>
They should study and disseminate experience and lessons
learned from developed countries in such a process, and good
practice from developing countries as well, so that developing
countries can adopt the most suitable approaches and improve
social and structural systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
The institutions are also urged to put more emphasis on getting
things done rather than mere deliberations.
</P>
<P>
"Increased concessional resources should be provided to
developing countries to meet their needs in their endeavor to
solve social problems," Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
On international trade, Xiang said he welcomes the involvement
of the World Bank to provide developing countries with
intellectual supporting services in the new round of multilateral
trade negotiations at the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"We also encourage the bank to help developing countries in
risk management during trade liberalization through well-targeted
services," he said.
</P>
<P>
On poverty reduction and debt relief for poor countries, the
Chinese minister said the institutions should focus their efforts
on economic growth in developing countries through resource
transfers and the redistribution of production factors in favor of
the poor.
</P>
<P>
"Developed countries have their obligation to increase official
development assistance aimed at poverty reduction," he added.
</P>
<P>
Xiang expressed his hope that major developed countries would
demonstrate their political willingness by promptly putting in
place additional financial resources required for the enhanced
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work on Second Yangtze River Bridge Proceeds Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 28 (Xinhua)-- The four-year construction of
the Second Yangtze River Bridge is going on smoothly in Nanjing,
the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, according to
information provided by bridge-construction headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is situated 11 km downstream from the world-famous
Nanjing Bridge and connects with Baguazhou Island, the third-
largest island on the Yangtze. Thus far, half the total budget of
3.19 billion yuan (384 million U.S. dollars) has been spent on the
project.
</P>
<P>
The 21.197 km new bridge includes the Beicha and Nancha bridges.
The Nancha Bridge, 2.958 km long, is a cable-stayed bridge with a
main span of 628 meters, the longest of its kind in China, and the
Beicha Bridge is a 2.212-km pre-stressed concrete structure.
</P>
<P>
The new bridge, or the No.2 Yangtze Bridge at Nanjing, has a
road surface of 32 meters, and is 33.5 meters at its bed, with six
lanes designed for speeds up to 100 km per hour. It is scheduled
for completion by July 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is expected to help ease the traffic jam on the
existing Nanjing Bridge and help the economic development of
Jiangsu and neighboring provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
