<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Drops in Nepal: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment
(FDI) inflows in Nepal in 1998 is estimated to remain much below
the 1997 level, according to a world investment report.
</P>
<P>
The World Investment Report 1999: Foreign Direct Investment and
the Challenge of Development published Monday said FDI in Nepal is
just 9 million dollars in 1998, which is much lower than 23
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
FDI in Nepal had gradually increased from four million dollars
in 1993 to six, five, 19, and 23 million dollars in 1994, 1995,
1996 and 1997 respectively. The average of FDI inflow for Nepal
from 1987 to 1992 was two million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the FDI rose by almost 40 percent to over 640 billion
U.S. dollars in the whole world last year.
</P>
<P>
The FDI inflow in 44 least developed countries of the world in
1998 increased to 2,948 million dollars, 468 million dollars
higher than the previous year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The FDI among the least developed countries from South, East
and Southeast Asia however went down by 28 million dollars to 558
million dollars from 1997.
</P>
<P>
The FDI in South, East, and Southeast Asia also went down
significantly from 87,835 million dollars in 1997 to 77,277
million dollars in 1998. This figure is even less than 79,397
million dollars of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
