<HEADLINE> China Urges IAEA to Help Curb Nuclear Proliferation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official has
urged the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to continue
with its efforts to make certain countries sign international
treaties on nuclear proliferation prevention.
</P>
<P>
At the opening here Monday of the 43rd annual conference of the
United Nations nuclear watchdog agency, Zhang Huazhu, chairman of
the China Atomic Energy Authority, said that it goes against the
trend of peace and development for some countries to continue
developing nuclear weapons and refuse joining the Comprehensive
Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and the Treaty on the Non-proliferation of
Nuclear Weapons.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA should push those countries to sign the treaties as
soon as possible and to take concrete measures in easing tension,
not only for the sake of regional and global peace and security
but also for the sake of their own benefit.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also said that the IAEA should continue to support the
development of nuclear power generation so as to reduce the
greenhouse gas emission.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA meeting will end on Friday. 
</P>
