<HEADLINE> Inter-country Meeting on Leprosy Elimination Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- An inter-country meeting of
national program managers for leprosy elimination is being held
here to find ways and means to reach the global goal of
eliminating the disease by the year 2000 and to expedite work in
drawing projects for 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, which began Monday, is attended by
leprosy elimination project managers of nine Southeast Asian
countries, delegates of international non-governmental
organizations (NGO) including those of the Netherlands, the
United States and Japan as well as representatives of the World
Health Organization (WHO) Headquarters in Geneva and WHO Southeast
Asia region.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Myanmar Health Minister Major-General
Ket Sein said there is a marked reduction of registered prevalence
rate in Myanmar as well as other countries with the detection of
new cases and putting them under Multi-Drug Therapy (MDT), leading
to total "cure".
</P>
<P>
With every country accelerating their activities to achieve
goals of leprosy elimination, the leprosy prevalence rate of most
countries is approaching 1 per 10,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Myanmar is prepared to conduct national
leprosy eradication campaign activities in coming October and
November.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is said to be one of the countries in which leprosy is
endemic. The country initiated leprosy control project activities
in 1951 which were gradually expanded to cover all townships in
1969.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the WHO and the UNICEF provided assistance for the
implementation of the program from 1956 to 1982 and international
NGOs also extended help in strengthening the manpower from 1967 to
1976.
</P>
<P>
With the recommendation of WHO, MDT was started in 1988 and 100
percent MDT coverage was achieved at the end of 1995 for the whole
 country.
</P>
<P>
Although leprosy is still endemic in Myanmar, every effort is
being made to implement and provide an integrated MDT service to
reach the global goal of leprosy elimination by the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
