<DOCNO> XIE19990928.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provincial Party Secretary Speaks About Poverty-Relief In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 28 (Xinhua) -- In the early 1970s, Premier
Zhou Enlai felt so sorry when he heard a report on poverty in
Gansu Province that he was in tears.
</P>
<P>
But the average per capita income of farmers there has gone
from 50 yuan (6 U.S. dollars) in 1949 to 1,393 yuan in 1998 and
more than 10 million farmers have solved the basic food and
clothing problem in the past 17 years, according to Sun Ying, the
Party secretary of this northwestern Chinese province.
</P>
<P>
Sun cites the reforms and opening up policy initiated in the
late 1970s and Party and State leaders' concern for Gansu as the
main reasons for this change.
</P>
<P>
Gansu is a land-locked, arid region that has historically been
one of the country's largest poor provinces. The number of poor
farmers with an annual per capita income of less than 200 yuan was
12.54 million 17 years ago, or 74.83 percent of the province's
rural population.
</P>
<P>
The State has spent heavily on poverty-relief work in the
province's 20 counties in the central part and 19 counties in the
Hexi Corridor since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The Hexi Corridor has now become one of China's key grain
production areas and the poor and backward situation in central
Gansu has changed remarkably. The number of impoverished people
went from 12.54 million in 1982 to 1.76 million by the end of 1998
and farmers' annual average per capita income in 53 counties
increased 13.7 percent while per capita grain share climbed from
257 kg. in 1982 to 327 kg. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sun explains that the relocation of more than 540,000 people
and labor service outside the province have helped the poverty-
relief efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
