<HEADLINE> Smuggled African Ivory Seized in Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in the
Chinese city of Tianjin recently discovered 83 pieces of smuggled
African ivory in a shipment of equipment of an engineering company
that was being returned from abroad for repairs.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that this is the first case of its kind in
Tianjin. The items were found packed in an air compressor, a fan,
and an engine tank.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary investigation showed that the items were bought
at a low price by the company's employees in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The African elephant is on the verge of extinction and is under
protection in most parts of the world. China signed an
international treaty protecting the animal in January, 1981. At a
conference in Lausanne, Switzerland in October, 1989, trade in
African ivory was banned.  
</P>
