<HEADLINE> Thailand to Contribute 1,500 Troops for Peacekeeping Force in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has finally agreed
to send 1,500 troops to East Timor, Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The final decision came after a meeting, on Monday, between
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, also defense minister, and the
military top brass led by gen. Mongkol Ampornpisit, supreme
commander of the Thai armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a slight drop from 1,778 troops
originally planned. It was reported that Chuan wanted to send only
as many as necessary to join the international peacekeeping force
in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Mongkol was quoted as saying on Monday that the government
would initially shoulder the expenses for the Thai contingent
estimated at about 100 million baht (2.5 million U.S. dollars) a
month. Thailand would be reimbursed later by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Thai troops were not going to East Timor to kill or harm
anyone, but to secure communication lines, to help East Timorese
in their reconstruction work, and to restore law and order, Gen.
Mongkol said.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 33 Thai soldiers left for Darwin of
Australia to join an advance multinational peacekeeping force in
East Timor. The second batch of 300 Thai combat soldiers will
leave Bangkok this Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai troops are to be based in Baucau, East Timor's second
largest city after the capital Dili. 
</P>
</TEXT>
