<HEADLINE> Chinese Patent Law To Be Amended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Patent Law enacted 15
years ago is set to be amended soon, according to officials with
the National People's Congress and the State Intellectual Property
Office (SIPO).
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee will review the revision draft
before the end of this year. It is now being studied by the State
Council, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The revision is expected to simplify application procedures of
patents, offer strengthened protection for patent holders and
adapt the Patent Law to the Patent Co-operation Treaty, Ma
Lianyuan, SIPO deputy director, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
More serious punishment stipulations have been adopted in the
draft to crack down on infringement of patent rights, and patent
offices are allowed to investigate such cases, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Usually applicants have to wait for months and even years to
know if their applications are approved due to the complicated
application rules and the rapid increase of applications, which
rose over seven times in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
For example, the telecommunications and computer sectors have
over 4,500 and 4,200 applications that are waiting for review,
which will take all current appraisers 10 years to finish.
</P>
<P>
At present, the office has taken additional measures to speed
up the review process, officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
