<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Sector Marks 50th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials and
executives of China's insurance industry gathered here Monday to
celebrate the 50th founding anniversary of the People's Republic
of China and the sector's 50 years of development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Ma Yongwei, chairman of the China
Insurance Regulatory Commission, said the country's insurance
sector has witnessed great achievements in the last 50 years,
despite the serious setbacks of the 1960s and 1970s when domestic
insurance was suspended.
</P>
<P>
Since the country's reform and opening up in the late 1970s,
the insurance sector has been growing rapidly. Official figures
show that insurer's premium income has been growing at an annual
rate of 38 percent, much higher than China's gross domestic
product (GDP) growth rate during the same period.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the industry's total premium income hit 124.7 billion
yuan, nearly 200 times that of 1980.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 to 1986, the People's Insurance Company of China was
the country's only insurer. But by the end of last year, there
were 25 insurance firms, including five joint ventures and seven
solely funded by foreign insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
Ma said the prosperity of the insurance sector in recent years
is the result of rapid economic and social development in China,
but by the same token, the insurance sector also contributed
greatly to economic development and social stability.
</P>
<P>
From 1989 to 1998, China's insurance firms paid out 260 billion
yuan in liabilities. As a result of the severe flooding that
struck China in 1998, insurers paid more than three billion yuan
for damages suffered by their clients.
</P>
<P>
The chairman expressed the belief that with the establishment
of the socialist market economy system in China, the insurance
sector will have a still brighter future and contribute more to
the nation's development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
